 low C = 7.6\n|Feb low C = 7.0\n|Mar low C = 8.4\n|Apr low C = 10.1\n|May low C = 12.1\n|Jun low C = 15.2\n|Jul low C = 17.1\n|Aug low C = 17.5\n|Sep low C = 16.0\n|Oct low C = 13.4\n|Nov low C = 10.1\n|Dec low C = 8.0\n|year low C = 11.8\n|Jan avg record low C = 3.2\n|Feb avg record low C = 2.8\n|Mar avg record low C = 3.9\n|Apr avg record low C = 6.0\n|May avg record low C = 8.3\n|Jun avg record low C = 11.7\n|Jul avg record low C = 13.8\n|Aug avg record low C = 14.4\n|Sep avg record low C = 12.2\n|Oct avg record low C = 8.7\n|Nov avg record low C = 5.2\n|Dec avg record low C = 3.3\n|year avg record low C = 1.9\n|Jan precipitation mm = 113.2\n|Feb precipitation mm = 97.8\n|Mar precipitation mm = 87.0\n|Apr precipitation mm = 80.6\n|May precipitation mm = 63.6\n|Jun precipitation mm = 57.1\n|Jul precipitation mm = 32.1\n|Aug precipitation mm = 43.2\n|Sep precipitation mm = 49.1\n|Oct precipitation mm = 88.8\n|Nov precipitation mm = 131.5\n|Dec precipitation mm = 100.9\n|year precipitation mm = 944.9\n|source 1 = M\u00e9t\u00e9o Climat<ref>{{cite web |url=http://meteo-climat-bzh.dyndns.org/relevmois-557-12-2016.php |title=M\u00e9t\u00e9o climat stats - Gij\u00f3n |accessdate= 7 February 2017}}</ref>\n|date=February 2017\n}}\n\n== Districts ==\nGij\u00f3n is divided in six districts:<ref>[http://distritos.gijon.es/page/8574-consejos-de-distrito Consejos de Distrito Gij\u00f3n City Hall website]</ref> Center, East, South, West, El Llano and Rural. In this last one, all the [[Peri-urbanisation|peri-urban]] zone and the [[Parish (administrative division)|rural parishes]] are integrated.\n\n===Neighborhoods and parishes===\n[[File:Parroquies de Xix\u00f3n numberaes.png|thumb|400px|Gij\u00f3n parishes]]\n[[File:Playa san lorenzo desembocadura piles.JPG|thumb|San Lorenzo beach]]\n[[File:024 Plaza del Marqu\u00e9s (Gij\u00f3n), amb el Palacio de Revillagigedo i la Fuente de Pelayo.jpg|thumb|Revillagigedo Palace and [[Pelagius of Asturias|King Pelagius]] statue]]\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" style=\"width:50%\" |\n;Center district:\n* Centro\n* [[Cimavilla]]\n* Laviada\n;Eastern district:\n* L'Arena\n* El Bibio\n* Ceares\n* El Coto\n* Las Mestas\n* Viesques\n;El Llano district:\n* El Llano\n;South district:\n* Contrueces\n* Montevil\n* Nuevo Gij\u00f3n\n* Perchera-La Bra\u00f1a\n* Pol\u00edgono de Pumar\u00edn\n* Pumar\u00edn\n* [[Roces (Gij\u00f3n)|Roces]] (22)\n* Santa B\u00e1rbara\n;Western district:\n* La Calzada\n* [[Jove, Gij\u00f3n|Jove]] (6)\n* [[Trema\u00f1es]] (21)\n* Natahoyo\n* Moreda\n|valign=\"top\" style=\"width:50%\" |\n;Rural district:\n* [[L'Abad\u00eda Cenero]] (19)\n* [[Cabue\u00f1es]] (9)\n* [[Caldones]] (11)\n* [[Castiello Bernueces]] (24)\n* [[Deva (Gij\u00f3n)|Deva]] (10)\n* [[Fano (Gij\u00f3n)|Fano]] (13)\n* [[Fresno (Gij\u00f3n)|Fresno]] (3)\n* [[Granda (Gij\u00f3n)|Granda]] (23)\n* [[La Pedrera (Gij\u00f3n)|La Pedrera]] (17)\n* [[Llavandera]] (14)\n* [[Leorio/Llorio]] (16)\n* [[Puao]] (4)\n* [[Porceyo]] (20)\n* [[Ruedes]] (18)\n* [[Samart\u00edn de G\u00fcerces]] (15)\n* [[San Andr\u00e9s de los Tacones]] (2)\n* [[Santurio]] (26)\n* [[Ser\u00edn]] (1)\n* [[Somi\u00f3]] (8)\n* [[Valdorn\u00f3n]] (12)\n* [[Vega (Gij\u00f3n)|Vega]] (25)\n* [[Veri\u00f1a]] (5)\n|}\n\n== Demography ==\n{{Historical populations\n| title= Population of Gij\u00f3n\n| percentages = pagr\n| 1857 | 23621\n| 1860 | 24802\n| 1877 | 30591\n| 1887 | 35170\n| 1897 | 43392\n| 1900 | 45544\n| 1910 | 55248\n| 1920 | 57573\n| 1930 | 78239\n| 1940 | 101341\n| 1950 | 110985\n| 1960 | 124714\n| 1970 | 187612\n| 1981 | 255969\n| 1991 | 260267\n| 2001 | 269270\n| 2011 | 277559\n| 2017 | 272365\n| 2018 | 271843\n| 2019 | 271780\n|footnote=From 1998 to present, population as of each January 1st\n|source = [http://www.ine.es/inebaseweb/libros.do?tntp=71807 INE]\n}}According to the 2013 Municipal Population Register (INE), the council had 275,274 inhabitants, of which 145,290 are women and 129,984 are men. The parish of Gij\u00f3n itself has 260 944 inhabitants. \n\nThe municipal population grew remarkably throughout the 20th century, especially between the 1960s and 1980s, a period in which it doubled. Starting in the 1990s, growth stagnated, reflecting the similar slowdown at the national level of Spain. However, due to immigration, both from other Asturias councils and from abroad, the population started to increase again at the turn of the 21st century. \n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Universidad Laboral gijon.jpg|thumb|[[Universidad Laboral de Gij\u00f3n]], today cultural center]]\n[[File:Gijon Iglesia San Pedro Apostol.jpg|thumb|San Pedro church]]\n[[File:Gijon - Antiguo Banco de Gij\u00f3n 01.JPG|thumb|right|The former Banco de Gij\u00f3n]]Gij\u00f3n is the cultural centre of the region of Asturias. Cultural activities are carried out throughout the year, which increase considerably in the summer months, especially in August due to the Feast of the Assumption, with parties, music and theater. This complements the continuous programming of the Teatro Municipal Jovellanos (Jovellanos Municipal Theater). The various festivities carried out in Gij\u00f3n include:\n\n* The Iberoamerican Book Fair, in May\n* The [[Semana Negra]] in July\n* The Feria Internacional de Muestras de Asturias\n* The [[Gij\u00f3n International Film Festival]]\n\nThe [[Universidad Laboral de Gij\u00f3n]], completed in 1955, contains the [[LABoral Centro de Arte y Creaci\u00f3n Industrial]] (Laboral Center of Art and Industrial Creation). The center was inaugurated on March 30, 2007 as an interdisciplinary space to promote artistic exchange and foster the relationship between society, art, science, technology and the creative industries. \n\nIn recent years, Gij\u00f3n has become a stop city for the [[Cirque du Soleil]]. The performances of the Cirque du Soleil have been very successful in the city. In July 2004, Saltimbanco arrived and in the summer of 2007, they presented Alegr\u00eda in Gij\u00f3n, the first time that this tour stopped in northern Spain. During the summer of 2009, Cirque du Soleil returned to Gij\u00f3n with the Varekai show. \n\n=== Film ===\n[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Garci]] filmed most of the footage from the film ''[[Begin the Beguine (film)|Volver a empezar]]'' in the city during the early 1980s. The film would later win an Academy Award for Best Foreign Film. In the early 1990s there was a boom in indie music bands in the town, which became known as the \"Xix\u00f3n Sound\". The comedy [[Mortadelo & Filemon: The Big Adventure]] was also filmed in part in the City of Culture of Gij\u00f3n. In 2009, the Laboral and its surroundings were converted to the University of Oxford for Fernando Gonz\u00e1lez Molina's film, [[Brain Drain (film)|Brain Drain]].\n\n=== Museums and art galleries ===\n* [[Museum of the Asturian People]]\n* [[Gij\u00f3n Railway Museum|Railway museum of Asturias]]\n* [[Nicanor Pi\u00f1ole museum]]\n* [[Roman Terms museum of Campo Vald\u00e9s]]\n* [[Juan Barjola Museum of Painting|Juan Barjola Museum]] (A museum about a local painter, also interested in [[avant-garde]] art)\n* [[Evaristo Valle museum]] (Local painter museum placed in a mansion at the outskirts)\n* [[International Bagpipe Museum]] contains [[bagpipe]]s from around the world, focusing on the [[Asturian language|Asturian]] musical heritage and bagpipes.\n* [[Atlantic botanical garden]]\n* Archaeological park [[Campa Torres]].\n* Revillagigedo Palace and museum (At Marqu\u00e9s square, near the City Hall)\n* [[Gij\u00f3n Aquarium]]\n* [[Roman Town of Veranes]]\n* [[LABoral Centro de Arte y Creaci\u00f3n Industrial]] (An exhibition center for contemporary art, science, technology and advanced visual industries)\n\n===Universities===\nThere are two campuses located in Gij\u00f3n, one of the [[University of Oviedo]] and other of the [[National University of Distance Education]].\n\n====University of Oviedo====\n* [[Gij\u00f3n Polytechnic School of Engineering]].\nMechanical Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Electronic Engineering, Computers and Systems Engineering, Chemical Engineering and Telecommunication Engineering.\n* School of Civil Navy.\n* Faculty of Commerce, Tourism and Social Sciences \"Jovellanos\".\nPublic Administration and Management, Trade and Marketing, Tourism and Social work.\n\n====National University of Distance Education (UNED)====\nGij\u00f3n also has a delegation of the [[National University of Distance Education|UNED]], where different disciplines can be studied by distance.\n\n== Sports ==\n[[File:ElMolinonSportingvsAthletic30-10-11.jpg|thumb|[[Estadio El Molin\u00f3n]], in a game of Sporting de Gij\u00f3n in [[La Liga]].]]\n{{See also|Category:Sport in Gij\u00f3n}}\nIn team sports, Gij\u00f3n's professional [[Association football|football]] team, [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n]], currently plays in the Spanish [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]]. [[CP Gij\u00f3n Solimar]] is one of the most important women's [[roller hockey (quad)|roller hockey]] teams in Europe as it is five times champion of the [[CERH Women's European Cup|European Cup]].\n\n[[C\u00edrculo Gij\u00f3n]] is the main [[basketball]] team of the city, and plays in Spanish basketball [[LEB Plata|third tier]]. [[Gij\u00f3n Baloncesto]], folded in 2009, was the most important team ot this sport in Gij\u00f3n, and played four seasons in the [[Liga ACB]], the most important national league in Europe.\n\n[[CSI Gij\u00f3n]] is Spain's official [[show jumping]] [[horse show]] which is held annually in [[Las Mestas Sports Complex|Gij\u00f3n's equestrian facility]].\n  \nThere is also a private [[sports club]] in Gij\u00f3n with more than 33,000 members, [[Real Grupo de Cultura Covadonga]], the biggest club in Asturias. Its [[Real Grupo de Cultura Covadonga (handball)|handball section]] plays in the third division, where also plays [[AB Gij\u00f3n Jovellanos]], and its women's volleyball team plays also in the Spanish second league.\n\nNot far from Gij\u00f3n, there are several [[ski resorts]] in [[Asturias]], the main being [[Valgrande-Pajares]].\n\nThe city's [[marina]] houses an important fleet of yachts and is the base for many [[water sports]], being [[Royal Astur Yacht Club]] the most important [[yacht club]] in town.\n\n===Sports centers===\nThe biggest sport centers in Gij\u00f3n are [[Estadio El Molin\u00f3n]], with 30,000 seats, [[Plaza de Toros de El Bibio]] with 12,000 and [[Palacio de Deportes de Gij\u00f3n|Palacio de Deportes]] with 5,000 seats. Games were played in town during the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nThe city has in total 13 public sport centers (in Spanish: ''Centros Municipales Integrados'') with swimming pools, gyms and [[saunas]]. Swimming pools are free for children up to age 14.\n\n== Economy ==\nFor much of the 20th century the town was heavily dependent on mature heavy industries, but at the end of the [[Francoism]], [[tertiary sector]] employment began to expand rapidly along with the city's population which by 2007 stood officially at 277,897 for Gij\u00f3n proper, and approximately 380,000 for the total Gij\u00f3n agglomeration.\n\nThe port is at the center of many of the local businesses.  Apart from directly port related activities, the economy is based on tourism, steel ([[Arcelor]]), other metallurgy, livestock rearing and fisheries.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Airports===\nGij\u00f3n is served by [[Asturias Airport]], about {{convert|38|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from the center of the city; it is located in the municipality of Castrillon.\nThe airport is connected to the city by the A-8 motorway, the N-632 national highway and scheduled bus service ([[ALSA (bus company)|Alsa]]).\n\n===Seaport===\n{{Main|El Musel}}\nThe service offered by LD Lines has been canceled in Gij\u00f3n. The closest Ferry services are now in [[Santander, Cantabria|Santander]] and [[Bilbao]]. However, Gij\u00f3n still has a good freight service by [[El Musel]]\n\n===Public transport===\nGij\u00f3n currently has 18 bus lines<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bus.gijon.es/page/146-lineas-y-servicios|title=L\u00edneas y Servicios en Bus Gij\u00f3n|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=Bus Gij\u00f3n|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and four more {{lang|es|B\u00faho}} (owl) lines. The [[Night service (public transport)|owl services]] work on Friday and Saturday nights, and daily in the months of July and August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bus.gijon.es/page/153-lineas-buho|title=L\u00ednes b\u00faho del Bus Gij\u00f3n|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=Bus Gij\u00f3n|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Railway===\nThe city is served by the [[Gij\u00f3n Railway Station]].\n\n===Roads and highways===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Type !! Name !! Alternate name !! Itinerary\n|-\n| rowspan=7| [[Highways in Spain|Highway]] || {{jct|country=ESP|A|A-8}} || Autov\u00eda del Cant\u00e1brico || Baamonde \u2013 ''Gij\u00f3n'' \u2013 [[Llanes]] \u2013 [[Torrelavega]] \u2013 Solares \u2013 [[Bilbao]] \u2013 [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n|-\n| {{jct|country=ESP|A|A-66}} || Autov\u00eda Ruta de la Plata || ''Gij\u00f3n'' \u2013 [[Oviedo]] \u2013 [[Mieres]] \u2013 [[Le\u00f3n, Spain|Le\u00f3n]] \u2013 [[Benavente, Zamora|Benavente]] \u2013 [[Zamora, Spain|Zamora]] \u2013 [[Salamanca]] \u2013 [[B\u00e9jar]] \u2013 [[Plasencia (C\u00e1ceres)|Plasencia]] \u2013 [[M\u00e9rida, Spain|M\u00e9rida]] \u2013 [[Almendralejo]] \u2013 [[Sevilla]]\n|-\n| {{jct|country=ESP|A|AS-I}} || Autov\u00eda Minera || ''Gij\u00f3n'' \u2013 [[Pola de Siero]] \u2013 [[Langreo]] \u2013 [[Mieres]]\n|-\n| {{jct|country=ESP|A|AS-II}} || Autov\u00eda Industrial || ''Gij\u00f3n'' \u2013 [[Llanera, Spain|Lugo de Llanera]] \u2013 [[Oviedo]]\n|-\n| GJ-10 || Interior [[ring road]] || Gij\u00f3n seaport ([[El Musel]])  \u2013 Pumar\u00edn \u2013 El Llano\n|-\n| GJ-20 || Western [[ring road]] || GJ-81 (Autopista Acceso Sur a Gij\u00f3n) \u2013 [[Trema\u00f1es]] \u2013 Gij\u00f3n seaport ([[El Musel]])\n|-\n| {{jct|country=ESP