ision Song Contest|then-Eurovision rules]], the top ten non-[[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big Four]] countries from the previous year along with the Big Four automatically qualified for the Grand Final without having to compete in semi-finals. For example, if Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the 11th and 12th spots were advanced to next year's Grand Final along with all countries ranked in the top ten.}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2007}}\n|[[DQ (singer)|DQ]]\n|English\n|\"[[Drama Queen (DQ song)|Drama Queen]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|19\n|align=center|45\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2008}}\n|[[Simon Mathew]]\n|English\n|\"[[All Night Long (Simon Mathew song)|All Night Long]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|60\n|bgcolor=\"#C96\" align=center|3\n|bgcolor=\"#C96\" align=center|112\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2009}}\n|[[Niels Brinck]]\n|English\n|\"[[Believe Again (Niels Brinck song)|Believe Again]]\"\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|74\n|align=center|8\n|align=center|69\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2010}}\n|[[Christina Chan\u00e9e|Chan\u00e9e]] & [[Tomas N'evergreen|N'evergreen]]\n|English\n|\"[[In a Moment Like This]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|149\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|101\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2011}}\n|[[A Friend in London]]\n|English\n|\"[[New Tomorrow]]\"\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|134\n|bgcolor=\"silver\" align=center|2\n|bgcolor=\"silver\" align=center|135\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012}}\n|[[Soluna Samay]]\n|English\n|\"[[Should've Known Better (Soluna Samay song)|Should've Known Better]]\"\n|align=center|23\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|63\n|-bgcolor=\"gold\"\n!{{Escyr|2013}}\n|[[Emmelie de Forest]]\n|English\n|\"[[Only Teardrops]]\"\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|281\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|167\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2014}}\n|[[Basim (singer)|Basim]] \n|English\n|\"[[Clich\u00e9 Love Song]]\"\n|align=center|9 \n|align=center|74\n|colspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"-9999\" {{N/A|Host country}}{{efn|name=note3|If a country had won the previous year, they did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year.}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2015}}\n|[[Anti Social Media]]\n|English\n|\"[[The Way You Are (Anti Social Media song)|The Way You Are]]\"\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|33\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2016}}\n|[[Lighthouse X]]\n|English\n|\"[[Soldiers of Love (Lighthouse X song)|Soldiers of Love]]\"\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|34\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2017}}\n|[[Anja Nissen]]\n|English\n|\"[[Where I Am (song)|Where I Am]]\"\n|align=center|20\n|align=center|77\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|101\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2018}}\n|[[Rasmussen (singer)|Rasmussen]]\n|English\n|\"[[Higher Ground (Rasmussen song)|Higher Ground]]\"\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|226\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|204\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2019}}\n|[[Leonora (singer)|Leonora]]\n|English, [[French language|French]]{{efn|Also contains phrases in [[German language|German]] and Danish.}}\n|\"[[Love Is Forever (Leonora song)|Love Is Forever]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|120\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|94\n|-bgcolor=\"#87A96B\"\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|2020}}}}{{Efn|The 2020 contest was cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|[[Ben & Tan]]\n|English \n|\"[[Yes (Ben & Tan song)|Yes]]\"\n|colspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Cancelled}}\n|}\n\n;<small>'''NOTES''':\n:a. {{note|a}} In 1996 Denmark failed to qualify for the contest. There was an audio only pre-qualification round for all countries (excluding hosts Norway). The official Eurovision site does not count 1996 in Denmark's list of appearances.\n:b. If a country had won the previous year, they did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year. In addition from 2004-2007, the top ten countries who were not members of the big four did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year. If, for example, Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the countries who placed 11th and 12th were advanced to the following year's grand final along with the rest of the top ten countries.</small>\n\n===Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest===\n{{further|Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Artist\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Language\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!colspan=\"4\"|At Congratulations\n!colspan=\"3\"|At Eurovision\n|-\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Final\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Semi\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Year\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Place\n!style=\"width:50px;\"|Points\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Olsen Brothers]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[English language|English]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Fly on the Wings of Love]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|6\n|111\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|{{Escyr|2000}}\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|1\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|195\n|}\n\n==Hostings==\n<!-- DO NOT add flagicons to the host city column.  This article is already about Denmark, so there is no need to highlight with {{flagicon}} that the city is in Denmark. This is in accordance with [[WP:ICONDECORATION]]. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n!Year\n!Location\n!Venue\n!Presenters\n!Photo\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1964}}\n|[[Copenhagen]]\n|[[Tivolis Koncertsal]]\n|[[Lotte W\u00e6ver]]\n|\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2001}}\n|Copenhagen\n|[[Parken Stadium]]\n|[[Natasja Crone Back]] and [[S\u00f8ren Pilmark]]\n|\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}\n|Copenhagen\n|[[B&W Hallerne]]\n|[[Lise R\u00f8nne]], [[Nikolaj Koppel]] and [[Johan Philip Asb\u00e6k|Pilou Asb\u00e6k]]\n|[[File:ESC2014 hosts 01 (crop).jpg|200px]]\n|{{center|<ref>Siim, Jarmo (2 September 2013): [http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=copenhagen_announced_as_host_city_of_eurovision_2014 \"Copenhagen announced as host city of Eurovision 2014\"]. Eurovision.tv. Retrieved 2 September 2013.</ref>}}\n|}\n\n=== Congratulations: