 a dark past'') CNN\n** [http://www.midnighteye.com/reviews/japdevil.shtml ''Japanese Devils''], Midnight Eye,\n* {{Cite video | people= The History Channel | date= 2000 | url= | title = Japanese War Crimes: Murder Under The Sun | medium = Video documentary (DVD & VHS) | location = | publisher= A & E Home Video}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Please alphabetize according to display title -->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070609112646/http://home.pacbell.net/fbaldie/Battling_Bastards_of_Bataan.html Battling Bastards of Bataan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080113004217/http://www.sjwar.org/ \"Biochemical Warfare \u2013 Unit 731\". Alliance for Preserving the Truth of Sino-Japanese War.] No date.\n* [http://www.warbirdforum.com/cannibal.htm \"Cannibalism\". Dan Ford, \"Japan at War, 1931\u20131945\"] September 2007.\n* [http://www.centurychina.com/wiihist/confess/index.html \"Confessions of Japanese war criminals\".] No date.\n* [https://fas.org/nuke/guide/japan/bw/ \"History of Japan's biological weapons program\"] [[Federation of American Scientists]], 2000-04-16\n* [http://www.systemclub.co.kr/ Ji Man-Won's website (in Korean)] Various dates.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/elsewhere/journalist/story/0,7792,1338296,00.html Justin McCurry, \"Japan's sins of the past\"] in ''[[The Guardian]]'', 2004-10-28\n* [https://www.archives.gov/iwg/ Nazi War Crimes and Japanese Imperial Government Records Interagency Working Group (IWG) ] U.S. [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA). No date.\n* [http://www.skycitygallery.com/japan/japan.html \"The Other Holocaust\"] No date.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041009171355/http://www.kimsoft.com/2002/jp-rape.htm \"Rape of Queen MIN\"] 2002\n* [http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.CHAP3.HTM R.J. Rummel, \"Statistics Of Japanese Democide: Estimates, Calculations, And Sources\" ] [[University of Hawaii]], 2002\n* [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/08/28/1030508070534.html Shane Green. \"The Asian Auschwitz of Unit 731\" ] in ''[[The Age]]'', 2002-08-29\n* [http://www.mofa.go.jp/announce/press/pm/murayama/9508.html \"Statement by Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama\"] 1995-08-15\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.technologyartist.com/unit_731/ |title=Steven Butler, \"A half century of denial: the hidden truth about Japan's unit 731\" |access-date=October 31, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061119053825/http://www.technologyartist.com/unit_731/ |archive-date=November 19, 2006 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }} in ''[[US News & World Report]]'' 1995-07-31\n* [http://histclo.com/essay/war/ww2/pow/pow-jap.html Japanese Treatment of World War II POWs]\n\n{{JapanEmpireNavbox}}\n{{IJA special research units}}\n{{World War II}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Japanese War Crimes}}\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in China]]\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in Korea]]\n[[Category:Historical negationism]]\n[[Category:History of Asia]]\n[[Category:Imperial Japanese Army]]\n[[Category:Imperial Japanese Navy]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Japanese culture]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes| ]]\n[[Category:Military history of Japan]]\n[[Category:War crimes committed by country]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAttacks on hospital ships:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_war_crimes"}
{"title_page": "Government Arsenal", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{update|date=May 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name   = Government Arsenal\n|nativename    = ''Pagawaan ng Punglo at Sandata''<br>\"Factory for Ammunition and Weapons\"<br/>\n|logo          = \n|logo_width    = \n|logo_caption  = \n|seal          = Government Arsenal, Department of National Defense (Philippines).svg\n|seal_width    = \n|seal_caption  = \n|image         = \n|image_width   = \n|image_caption  = \n|formed        = June 22, 1957\n|preceding1    = Creation of Republic Act 1884\n|preceding2    = \n|dissolved     = \n|superseding   = \n|jurisdiction  = \n|headquarters  = Camp General Antonio Luna, [[Limay, Bataan|Limay]], [[Bataan]], [[Philippines]]\n|employees     = \n|budget        = \n|chief1_name   = MGen Daniel R. Casabar, Jr (Ret.)\n|chief1_position = Government Arsenal Director\n|agency_type   = \n|parent_agency = [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]]\n|child1_agency = \n|website       = {{URL|www.arsenal.mil.ph}}\n|footnotes     = \n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   = Government Arsenal\n| logo   = \n| type   = [[State-owned company]]\n| foundation     = 1957\n| location       = Camp General Antonio Luna, [[Limay, Bataan|Limay]], [[Bataan]], [[Philippines]]\n| industry       = [[Arms industry|Defense]], Industrial\n| products       = Military and civilian products\n}}\n\nThe '''Government Arsenal''' ('''GA''') is an agency of the Philippine government under the [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]], responsible for the production of basic weaponry and ammunition for the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] (AFP), and  the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP), among others, and for the sale and export of products in excess of AFP/PNP requirements.\n\n==History==\nThe Government Arsenal (GA) is located on a 370-[[hectare]] defense industrial estate in Lamao, [[Limay, Bataan]], about 120&nbsp;km from [[Manila]] by land, 70&nbsp;km from [[Subic, Zambales|Subic]] and 90&nbsp;km from [[Clark Air Base|Clark]]. Just three km from the Port of Limay, the Arsenal is strategically situated near the [[Petron Corporation|Petron]] Bataan Refinery, the Bataan Combined Cycle Power Plant, the [[National Power Corporation]] Plant, the Petro-Chemical Complex, and the [[Freeport Area of Bataan|Freeport Area]] at [[Mariveles, Bataan]]. To sustain its operations, the GA presently maintains and operates 124 buildings and structures sprawled over 70 hectares of land.\n\nA creation of [[Republic Acts of the Philippines|Republic Act]] No. 1884 which was signed into law on June 22, 1957, the Arsenal is a line bureau under the [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]]. However, it was only about a decade later, on March 7, 1967, that a presidential proclamation on its present site at [[Limay, Bataan]] was declared. Accordingly, on October 12, 1967, the ground breaking materialized at the spot where the statue of [[Antonio Luna|General Antonio Luna]] now stands. Site preparations were subsequently undertaken by the 514th and 564th Engineering Construction Battalions of the 51st Engineering Brigade of the Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP). Construction of essential buildings and facilities then followed along with training abroad of selected military and newly hired civilian personnel on the manufacture of small arms ammunition (SAA).\n\nOn August 15, 1971, or fourteen (14) years after the enactment of Republic Act 1884, the first SAA cartridge rolled out of the GA's production assembly line. Three years later, the integrated SAA manufacture began, with all the components - case, primer, propellant powder, and bullet assembled into a complete cartridge - manufactured in the arsenal.\n\nAs a strategic resource, the arsenal is envisioned to be a center for defense industries to meet domestic requirements and supply the world market. In line with this vision, the GA explored in the early 1980s, the possibility of exporting excess production, improving ammunition technology and expanding the capability for weapons production as called for in its charter. However, the impediments under the then existing laws prevented any real progress in this direction.\n\n==Modernization==\n[[File:GA Marine Scout Sniper Rifle Variant 1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|GA-made [[Marine Scout Sniper Rifle|Marine Scout Sniper Rifles]] on display.]]\n\nOn February 23, 1995, Republic Act 7898, otherwise known as the [[AFP Modernization Act]], was enacted. Republic Act 7898 likewise provides for the modernization of the Government Arsenal for the development of production capabilities to enhance self-sufficiency in defense requirements. Specifically, Section 12 of this Act mandates that \"the government arsenal shall be utilized in the production of basic weapons, ammunition and other munitions for the use of the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] and the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP), and for the sale and export of products in excess of AFP/PNP requirements.\" Furthermore, the GA is authorized to use such production facilities as it may own or be provided under the law or as it may arrange under joint venture, co-production or similar arrangements with local and foreign entities.\n\nAs part of the modernization effort, the arsenal, through the Department of National Defense, issued an invitation to bid for a Multi-Station Bullet Assembly Machine for 5.56mm M193/M855 in August 2009.<ref name=\"bid\">{{cite web |title=Invitation to Apply for Eligibility and to Bid (IAEB): Multi-Station Bullet Assembly Machine for 5.56mm M193/M855 |url=http://www.dnd.gov.ph/DNDWEBPAGE_files/dndbac/ITB/ITEABSep09/ITAEB%20GA.pdf |publisher=Department of National Defense |date=2009-08-29 |accessdate=2009-12-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  This marks a significant expansion of existing production lines.\n\nAs of the most recent supplemental bulletin for the bid,<ref name=\"supp\">{{cite web |title=Supplemental bid bulletin Nr. GA 14SBAM-09-03 |url=http://www.dnd.gov.ph/DNDWEBPAGE_files/dndbac/SB/2009/NOV/GA14SBAM-09-03%20%2811-24-2009%29.pdf |publisher=Department of National Defense |date=2009-08-29 |accessdate=2009-12-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> bids for this acquisition were to have been opened on 4 December 2009.\n\n==Government Arsenal Modernization Act==\nIn July 1, 2010, Congressman Albert Garcia sponsored the House Bill 0076,<ref name=\"modbill\">{{cite web |title=House Bill 00076 |url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/download/basic_15/HB00076.pdf |publisher=House of Representatives, 15th Congress of the Philippines |date=2010-07-27 |accessdate=2011-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805151406/http://www.congress.gov.ph/download/basic_15/HB00076.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-05 }}</ref> also known as the \"Government Arsenal Modernization Act\". Congressmen Mel Sarmiento, Francis Ortega, and Leopoldo Bataoil are listed as co-sponsors. The bill sought to implement the following four-phase, 6.3 billion peso, modernization program:\n\n* '''Phase I - Enhancement of the Arsenal's Capacity in Production of Small Arms Ammunition'''\nProjected budget: One Billion Three Hundred Forty Million Pesos (P1.340B)\n\n''The Arsenal shall acquire various equipment necessary to enhance ts capability and increase its annual capacity in the production of Small Arms (ammunition) to a level where it can fully support the Small Arms Ammunition requirements of the AFP, PNP, and other government law enforcement agencies in accordance with its modernization objectives. Phase I shall be aimed at increasing its annual Small Arms Ammunition production to meet the overall Small Arms Ammunition requirements of all defense and law enforcement agencies.\n''\n* '''Phase II - Development of the Arsenal's Capability in Weapons Manufacture'''\nProjected budget: Two Billion Pesos (P2.0B) for a period of four years\n\n''The Arsenal shall acquire necessary equipment and technologies to develop its capabilities in the field of weapons manufacture to a level where it can truly perform its lawful mandate. The Arsenal shall likewise continuously conduct research and development activities in accordance with the spirit of Self-Reliant Defense Posture (SRDP) Program of the government in order to gain insights and finally develop technical capability in the manufacture of weapons that are vital to support the mission of the AFP, PNP and other law enforcement agencies.''\n\n* '''Phase III - Establishment of Various Munitions Testing Facilities'''\nProjected budget: Five Hundred Million Pesos (P500M)\n\n''The Arsenal shall be transformed from its present status as a mere small arms ammunition manufacturer into a multi-task-capable agency by establishing various facilities with necessary equipment and appropriate technology to hone and harness its technical know-how in the conduct of tests and evaluation of an assortment of defense material.''\n\n* '''Phase IV - Development of Arsenal's Capability to Manufacture Medium and Large Caliber Ammunition'''\nProjected budget: Four Hundred Ninety-two Million Pesos (P492M) for a period of five years\n\n''The Arsenal shall require suitable equipment and the attendant technology and establish facilities to develop its capability in the manufacturer of medium and large caliber ammunition.''\n\nThis bill has been pending with the House Committee on National Defense since July 27, 2010.<ref name=\"modbillstat\">{{cite web |title=Status of House Bill 00076 |url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/legis/search/hist_show.php?congress=15&save=1&journal=&switch=0&bill_no=HB00076 |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date=2010-07-27 |accessdate=2011-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008180916/http://www.congress.gov.ph/legis/search/hist_show.php?congress=15&save=1&journal=&switch=0&bill_no=HB00076 |archivedate=2012-10-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Headstamp code for ammunition==\n\nSmall arms ammunition manufactured by the Government Arsenal can be identified by the headstamp code: \"RPA\".<ref name=\"rpa\">{{cite web |title=International Ammunition Association, headstamp codes |url=http://cartridgecollectors.org/headstampcodes_bottom.htm#R |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> This acronym stands for \"Republic of the Philippines Arsenal\".\n\n==Images==\n\n{{Gallery\n| title        = Goverment Arsenal Ammunition\n| align        = center\n| footer       =\n| style        =\n| state        =\n| height       = 170\n| width        = 160\n| captionstyle =\n| File:.30 Carbine & .30-06 Springfield.jpg\n | alt1=\n | .30 Carbine & .30-06 Springfield\n| File:.38 Special & 9x19mm Parabellum.jpg\n | alt2=\n | .38 Special & 9x19mm Parabellum\n| File:.45 ACP Ball.jpg\n | alt3=\n | Cal .45, M1911, Ball\n| File:.45 ACP Training (Teflon-coated SWC & RN).jpg\n | alt4=\n | 45 ACP Training (Teflon-coated SWC & RN)\n| File:7.62\u00d737mm Musang cartridges on display.jpg\n | alt5=7.62\u00d737mm Musang cartridges\n | 7.62\u00d737mm Musang\n| File:5.56x45mm Ball (M193).jpg\n | alt6=\n | 5.56x45mm Ball (M193)\n| File:5.56x45mm Ball (M193), Match (55 gr & 69 gr).jpg\n | alt7=\n | 5.56x45mm Ball (M193), Match (55 gr & 69 gr)\n| File:5.56x45mm NATO (M855, SS109) & Blank.jpg\n | alt8=\n | 5.56x45mm NATO (M855, SS109) & Blank\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80).jpg\n | alt9=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80)\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80A).jpg\n | alt10=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80A)\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Blank.jpg\n | alt11=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Blank\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Match (168gr.).jpg\n | alt12=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Match (168 gr)\n| File:Government Arsenal Ammo Crates.jpg\n | alt13=\n | HDPE ammunition crates\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]]\n* [[GA Personal Defense Weapon|GA 10\" Personal Defense Weapon (PDW)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.arsenal.mil.ph/ GA Homepage]\n{{Department of National Defense of the Philippines}}\n\n{{commons category|Government Arsenal (GA)}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Military facilities in Bataan]]\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Government-owned and controlled corporations of the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{update|date=May 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name   = Government Arsenal\n|nativename    = ''Pagawaan ng Punglo at Sandata''<br>\"Factory for Ammunition and Weapons\"<br/>\n|logo          = \n|logo_width    = \n|logo_caption  = \n|seal          = Government Arsenal, Department of National Defense (Philippines).svg\n|seal_width    = \n|seal_caption  = \n|image         = \n|image_width   = \n|image_caption  = \n|formed        = June 22, 1957\n|preceding1    = Creation of Republic Act 1884\n|preceding2    = \n|dissolved     = \n|superseding   = \n|jurisdiction  = \n|headquarters  = Camp General Antonio Luna, [[Limay, Bataan|Limay]], [[Bataan]], [[Philippines]]\n|employees     = \n|budget        = \n|chief1_name   = MGen Daniel R. Casabar, Jr (Ret.)\n|chief1_position = Government Arsenal Director\n|agency_type   = \n|parent_agency = [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]]\n|child1_agency = \n|website       = {{URL|www.arsenal.mil.ph}}\n|footnotes     = \n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   = Government Arsenal\n| logo   = \n| type   = [[State-owned company]]\n| foundation     = 1957\n| location       = Camp General Antonio Luna, [[Limay, Bataan|Limay]], [[Bataan]], [[Philippines]]\n| industry       = [[Arms industry|Defense]], Industrial\n| products       = Military and civilian products\n}}\n\nThe '''Government Arsenal''' ('''GA''') is an agency of the Philippine government under the [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]], responsible for the production of basic weaponry and ammunition for the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] (AFP), and  the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP), among others, and for the sale and export of products in excess of AFP/PNP requirements.\n\n==History==\nThe Government Arsenal (GA) is located on a 370-[[hectare]] defense industrial estate in Lamao, [[Limay, Bataan]], about 120&nbsp;km from [[Manila]] by land, 70&nbsp;km from [[Subic, Zambales|Subic]] and 90&nbsp;km from [[Clark Air Base|Clark]]. Just three km from the Port of Limay, the Arsenal is strategically situated near the [[Petron Corporation|Petron]] Bataan Refinery, the Bataan Combined Cycle Power Plant, the [[National Power Corporation]] Plant, the Petro-Chemical Complex, and the [[Freeport Area of Bataan|Freeport Area]] at [[Mariveles, Bataan]]. To sustain its operations, the GA presently maintains and operates 124 buildings and structures sprawled over 70 hectares of land.\n\nA creation of [[Republic Acts of the Philippines|Republic Act]] No. 1884 which was signed into law on June 22, 1957, the Arsenal is a line bureau under the [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]]. However, it was only about a decade later, on March 7, 1967, that a presidential proclamation on its present site at [[Limay, Bataan]] was declared. Accordingly, on October 12, 1967, the ground breaking materialized at the spot where the statue of [[Antonio Luna|General Antonio Luna]] now stands. Site preparations were subsequently undertaken by the 514th and 564th Engineering Construction Battalions of the 51st Engineering Brigade of the Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP). Construction of essential buildings and facilities then followed along with training abroad of selected military and newly hired civilian personnel on the manufacture of small arms ammunition (SAA).\n\nOn August 15, 1971, or fourteen (14) years after the enactment of Republic Act 1884, the first SAA cartridge rolled out of the GA's production assembly line. Three years later, the integrated SAA manufacture began, with all the components - case, primer, propellant powder, and bullet assembled into a complete cartridge - manufactured in the arsenal.\n\nAs a strategic resource, the arsenal is envisioned to be a center for defense industries to meet domestic requirements and supply the world market. In line with this vision, the GA explored in the early 1980s, the possibility of exporting excess production, improving ammunition technology and expanding the capability for weapons production as called for in its charter. However, the impediments under the then existing laws prevented any real progress in this direction.\n\n==Modernization==\n[[File:GA Marine Scout Sniper Rifle Variant 1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|GA-made [[Marine Scout Sniper Rifle|Marine Scout Sniper Rifles]] on display.]]\n\nOn February 23, 1995, Republic Act 7898, otherwise known as the [[AFP Modernization Act]], was enacted. Republic Act 7898 likewise provides for the modernization of the Government Arsenal for the development of production capabilities to enhance self-sufficiency in defense requirements. Specifically, Section 12 of this Act mandates that \"the government arsenal shall be utilized in the production of basic weapons, ammunition and other munitions for the use of the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] and the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP), and for the sale and export of products in excess of AFP/PNP requirements.\" Furthermore, the GA is authorized to use such production facilities as it may own or be provided under the law or as it may arrange under joint venture, co-production or similar arrangements with local and foreign entities.\n\nAs part of the modernization effort, the arsenal, through the Department of National Defense, issued an invitation to bid for a Multi-Station Bullet Assembly Machine for 5.56mm M193/M855 in August 2009.<ref name=\"bid\">{{cite web |title=Invitation to Apply for Eligibility and to Bid (IAEB): Multi-Station Bullet Assembly Machine for 5.56mm M193/M855 |url=http://www.dnd.gov.ph/DNDWEBPAGE_files/dndbac/ITB/ITEABSep09/ITAEB%20GA.pdf |publisher=Department of National Defense |date=2009-08-29 |accessdate=2009-12-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  This marks a significant expansion of existing production lines.\n\nAs of the most recent supplemental bulletin for the bid,<ref name=\"supp\">{{cite web |title=Supplemental bid bulletin Nr. GA 14SBAM-09-03 |url=http://www.dnd.gov.ph/DNDWEBPAGE_files/dndbac/SB/2009/NOV/GA14SBAM-09-03%20%2811-24-2009%29.pdf |publisher=Department of National Defense |date=2009-08-29 |accessdate=2009-12-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> bids for this acquisition were to have been opened on 4 December 2009.\n\n==Government Arsenal Modernization Act==\nIn July 1, 2010, Congressman Albert Garcia sponsored the House Bill 0076,<ref name=\"modbill\">{{cite web |title=House Bill 00076 |url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/download/basic_15/HB00076.pdf |publisher=House of Representatives, 15th Congress of the Philippines |date=2010-07-27 |accessdate=2011-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805151406/http://www.congress.gov.ph/download/basic_15/HB00076.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-05 }}</ref> also known as the \"Government Arsenal Modernization Act\". Congressmen Mel Sarmiento, Francis Ortega, and Leopoldo Bataoil are listed as co-sponsors. The bill sought to implement the following four-phase, 6.3 billion peso, modernization program:\n\n* '''Phase I - Enhancement of the Arsenal's Capacity in Production of Small Arms Ammunition'''\nProjected budget: One Billion Three Hundred Forty Million Pesos (P1.340B)\n\n''The Arsenal shall acquire various equipment necessary to enhance ts capability and increase its annual capacity in the production of Small Arms (ammunition) to a level where it can fully support the Small Arms Ammunition requirements of the AFP, PNP, and other government law enforcement agencies in accordance with its modernization objectives. Phase I shall be aimed at increasing its annual Small Arms Ammunition production to meet the overall Small Arms Ammunition requirements of all defense and law enforcement agencies.\n''\n* '''Phase II - Development of the Arsenal's Capability in Weapons Manufacture'''\nProjected budget: Two Billion Pesos (P2.0B) for a period of four years\n\n''The Arsenal shall acquire necessary equipment and technologies to develop its capabilities in the field of weapons manufacture to a level where it can truly perform its lawful mandate. The Arsenal shall likewise continuously conduct research and development activities in accordance with the spirit of Self-Reliant Defense Posture (SRDP) Program of the government in order to gain insights and finally develop technical capability in the manufacture of weapons that are vital to support the mission of the AFP, PNP and other law enforcement agencies.''\n\n* '''Phase III - Establishment of Various Munitions Testing Facilities'''\nProjected budget: Five Hundred Million Pesos (P500M)\n\n''The Arsenal shall be transformed from its present status as a mere small arms ammunition manufacturer into a multi-task-capable agency by establishing various facilities with necessary equipment and appropriate technology to hone and harness its technical know-how in the conduct of tests and evaluation of an assortment of defense material.''\n\n* '''Phase IV - Development of Arsenal's Capability to Manufacture Medium and Large Caliber Ammunition'''\nProjected budget: Four Hundred Ninety-two Million Pesos (P492M) for a period of five years\n\n''The Arsenal shall require suitable equipment and the attendant technology and establish facilities to develop its capability in the manufacturer of medium and large caliber ammunition.''\n\nThis bill has been pending with the House Committee on National Defense since July 27, 2010.<ref name=\"modbillstat\">{{cite web |title=Status of House Bill 00076 |url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/legis/search/hist_show.php?congress=15&save=1&journal=&switch=0&bill_no=HB00076 |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date=2010-07-27 |accessdate=2011-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008180916/http://www.congress.gov.ph/legis/search/hist_show.php?congress=15&save=1&journal=&switch=0&bill_no=HB00076 |archivedate=2012-10-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Headstamp code for ammunition==\n\nSmall arms ammunition manufactured by the Government Arsenal can be identified by the headstamp code: \"RPA\".<ref name=\"rpa\">{{cite web |title=International Ammunition Association, headstamp codes |url=http://cartridgecollectors.org/headstampcodes_bottom.htm#R |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> This acronym stands for \"Republic of the Philippines Arsenal\".\n\n==Images==\n\n{{Gallery\n| title        = Goverment Arsenal Ammunition\n| align        = center\n| footer       =\n| style        =\n| state        =\n| height       = 170\n| width        = 160\n| captionstyle =\n| File:.30 Carbine & .30-06 Springfield.jpg\n | alt1=\n | .30 Carbine & .30-06 Springfield\n| File:.38 Special & 9x19mm Parabellum.jpg\n | alt2=\n | .38 Special & 9x19mm Parabellum\n| File:.45 ACP Ball.jpg\n | alt3=\n | Cal .45, M1911, Ball\n| File:.45 ACP Training (Teflon-coated SWC & RN).jpg\n | alt4=\n | 45 ACP Training (Teflon-coated SWC & RN)\n| File:7.62\u00d737mm Musang cartridges on display.jpg\n | alt5=7.62\u00d737mm Musang cartridges\n | 7.62\u00d737mm Musang\n| File:5.56x45mm Ball (M193).jpg\n | alt6=\n | Write a caption here\n| File:5.56x45mm Ball (M193), Match (55 gr & 69 gr).jpg\n | alt7=\n | 5.56x45mm Ball (M193), Match (55 gr & 69 gr)\n| File:5.56x45mm NATO (M855, SS109) & Blank.jpg\n | alt8=\n | 5.56x45mm NATO (M855, SS109) & Blank\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80).jpg\n | alt9=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80)\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80A).jpg\n | alt10=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Ball (M80A)\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Blank.jpg\n | alt11=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Blank\n| File:7.62\u00d751mm NATO Match (168gr.).jpg\n | alt12=\n | 7.62\u00d751mm NATO Match (168 gr)\n| File:Government Arsenal Ammo Crates.jpg\n | alt13=\n | HDPE ammunition crates\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Department of National Defense]]\n* [[GA Personal Defense Weapon|GA 10\" Personal Defense Weapon (PDW)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.arsenal.mil.ph/ GA Homepage]\n{{Department of National Defense of the Philippines}}\n\n{{commons category|Government Arsenal (GA)}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Military facilities in Bataan]]\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Government-owned and controlled corporations of the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Girder2139", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImages:Added caption to \"5.56x45mm Ball (M193)\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_Arsenal"}
{"title_page": "Lit (band)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Lit\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Lit band.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Lit performing at [[Mohegan Sun]] in [[Connecticut]] in 2005.\n| alias            = Razzle <small>(1988\u20131994)</small> {{nowrap|Stain <small>(1994\u20131996)</small>}}\n| origin           = [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], [[California]]<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\">{{cite book\n| first= Martin C.\n| last= Strong\n| year= 2000\n| title= The Great Rock Discography\n| edition= 5th\n| publisher= Mojo Books\n| location= Edinburgh\n| page= 575\n| isbn= 1-84195-017-3}}</ref>\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop punk]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\ncountry rock\n}}\n| years_active     = 1988\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n* [[DRT Entertainment|DRT]]\n* [[Megaforce Records|Megaforce]]\n}}\n| website          = {{url|litband.com}}\n| current_members  = Kevin Baldes<br>Ajay Popoff<br>Jeremy Popoff<br>Ryan Gillmor<br> Evan Kilbourne\n| past_members     = Sean Holland<br>Charles Ward<br>[[Allen Shellenberger]]<br>Chadd Anthony (Chad Benekos)<br>Nathan Walker<br>Terry Stirling Jr.\n}}\n\n'''Lit''' is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band, formed in 1988 in [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], [[California]]. They are best known for their song \"[[My Own Worst Enemy (song)|My Own Worst Enemy]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/lit-mn0000837886/biography|title=Lit - Biography|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|work=AllMusic|accessdate= March 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Pre-Lit (1986\u20131995)===\nJeremy Popoff and bassist Kevin Baldes met in 1986, and soon after, began playing music together. In 1987, Jeremy Popoff and Jerry Neel formed the band Strate Lace and performed three live shows together: The Troubador in Hollywood, The Waters Club in San Pedro, and a back-to-school party in a friend's back yard. Neel quit the band to pursue a career in the mortgage industry.\n\nLater on, high school friends Baldes (15 or 16 at the time) and Popoff's brother Ajay (14 at the time) formed the pop metal band Razzle in 1988 with Sean Holland. The lineup included Kevin Baldes (bass, vocals), Ajay Popoff (drums, percussion), Sean Holland (guitar), and Charles Ward (vocals). They performed their first show on June 26, 1988, at [[The Troubadour, West Hollywood|The Troubadour]]. In 1989, Ajay switched from drums to lead vocals, and the band added guitarist Jeremy Popoff and drummer [[Allen Shellenberger]]. Things began to come together in 1990, when the group released a demo tape and an EP entitled ''New Vibe Revolution'' in 1993.  Razzle dissolved in 1993 and became Stain in 1994, which had a much harder and heavier sound. They released a demo tape in 1995 and eventually signed with Malicious Vinyl in 1995. After finding out the name \"Stain\" was already owned, the band changed their name to Lit.\n\n===''Tripping the Light Fantastic'' (1996\u20131997)===\nOn April 1, 1997 the group released ''[[Tripping the Light Fantastic (album)|Tripping the Light Fantastic]]'' on the Malicious Vinyl [[record label]].<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> Malicious Vinyl went out of business shortly after ''Tripping the Light Fantastic'' was released, which left the band unsigned once again. They spent their time writing a new batch of songs and showcasing for various record labels until they signed with [[RCA Records]] in 1998.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/>\n\n===The RCA years (1998\u20132002)===\nThe group gained popularity with their second album ''[[A Place in the Sun (Lit album)|A Place in the Sun]]'', released in February 1999. ''A Place in the Sun'' yielded the [[hit single]], \"[[My Own Worst Enemy (Lit song)|My Own Worst Enemy]],\" which peaked at number 51 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]], topping the [[Modern Rock Tracks|Billboard Hot Modern Rock Tracks]] chart for a total of 12 weeks, and receiving a ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Music Award for the biggest modern rock song of 1999. It was followed by \"[[Zip-Lock (song)|Zip-Lock]]\" (which featured [[Blink-182]] in the [[music video|video]]) and \"[[Miserable (song)|Miserable]]\", the latter of which was among the top ten most played songs of 2000 and featured [[Pamela Anderson]] in the video, as a [[giantess]] who lets the band walk on different parts her body before eventually betraying and [[Vorarephilia|devouring]] them all. Shortly after, the album went [[music recording sales certification|platinum]] in the US and [[music recording sales certification|gold]] in Canada, becoming the band's best selling album. The band performed over 286 shows and toured worldwide in support of ''A Place in the Sun''. In addition to the [[Vans Warped Tour]] and a slot on [[Woodstock 1999]], the band toured with [[The Offspring]], [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]], and [[No Doubt]]. The band's tracks also appeared in soundtracks of ''[[Ready to Rumble]]'' and ''[[The Replacements (film)|The Replacements]]''.\n\nLit followed up ''A Place in the Sun'' with the 2001 release of ''[[Atomic (Lit album)|Atomic]]''. The new album steered away from the sound of their last [[pop punk]] album, resulting in a more mature yet ultimately less successful format. The band's highest charting single was \"[[Lipstick and Bruises]]\" which reached [[Top 40|Top 10]] on the [[Modern Rock Tracks|Billboard's Hot Modern Rock Tracks]]. Lit toured to support ''Atomic'' with [[Kid Rock]] and [[Butch Walker]]. The group was released from their contract with RCA Records in late 2002.\n\n===Self-titled album (2003\u20132007)===\nLit went on a small, intimate club tour in the fall of 2003 before releasing the self-titled ''Lit'' on the [[DRT Entertainment]] label on June 24, 2004. The single \"Looks Like They Were Right\" made it on the Top 40 charts. That year the group also put out its first long-form [[DVD]], ''All Access'', on November 16, 2004.\n\n===Death of Allen Shellenberger===\n\nOn May 5, 2008, Lit announced that their drummer Allen Shellenberger was diagnosed with a brain tumor. Shellenberger immediately underwent clinical trials, chemotherapy and radiation at the Cedars-Sinai Maxine Dunitz Neurosurgical Institute. It was discovered that the tumor was [[malignant glioma]] and was incurable. His treatments were documented in a piece on [[ABC World News Tonight]] that aired in the same month. Lit cancelled their scheduled tour dates with [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] due to Shellenberger's diagnosis. On July 26, 2008, Lit held a benefit concert for Allen at the [[House Of Blues]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. A number of bands performed including [[Sugar Ray]] and [[Handsome Devil (band)|Handsome Devil]]. [[No Doubt]] drummer [[Adrian Young]] filled in for Shellenberger for a couple of songs. Both drummers also played at the same time for a few songs. The concert was Allen's last show with Lit, as he died at the age of 39 from his tumor on August 13, 2009.<ref name=\"consequenceofsound.net\">{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/08/14/lit-drummer-allen-shellenberger-dead-at-39/|title=Lit drummer Allen Shellenberger dead at 39|accessdate=August 14, 2009|publisher=Consequenceofsound.net}}</ref>\n\n===''The View from the Bottom'' (2009\u20132015)===\nOn November 23, 2009, Lit played their first concert since Allen Shellenberger's death. Drum tech Nathan Walker, who had filled in for Shellenberger earlier that year, was now his successor on drums. They later announced that they had begun to work on a new album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=3954749&blogId=520152622 |title=Lit Update - 11/27/09 van Lit op Myspace |publisher=Blogs.myspace.com |date=November 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065936/http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view |archivedate=February 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010 during an interview with OC Talk Radio, Lit hinted that they would return to a major label for their next release. They also revealed their work on a new management deal, as well as performing new material live.\n\nIn September 2010, Kevin Baldes confirmed that Lit were in the studio, writing and recording their sixth studio album. The band worked with producer [[Marti Frederiksen]] ([[Aerosmith]], [[Def Leppard]], [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Faith Hill]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=3954749&blogId=539381684 |title=Featured Content on Myspace |publisher=Blogs.myspace.com |accessdate=April 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065936/http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view |archivedate=February 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe band reported that they were still in the studio recording in July 2011, and released a demo video titled \"You Tonight\". Lit announced in December 2011 that they were back in the studio with producer [[Butch Walker]] to finish their new album. It was also announced that the band had signed with [[Megaforce Records]] and would release their new album ''[[The View from the Bottom]]'' on June 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chinashopmag.com/2012/01/lit-teams-up-with-butch-walker/ |title=Lit Teams Up With Butch Walker: This is How Awesome is Made &#124; ChinaShop |publisher=Chinashopmag.com |date=January 2, 2012 |accessdate=April 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723231138/http://www.chinashopmag.com/2012/01/lit-teams-up-with-butch-walker/ |archive-date=July 23, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe first single, \"You Tonight,\" was released on iTunes on May 1, 2012, and a video for \"The Broken\" was released in August 2012.\n\nOn January 7, 2013, frontman Ajay Popoff told ''[[Loudwire]]'' that after Lit finished touring in support of ''The View from the Bottom'', they would begin writing their next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/a-jay-popoff-lit-this-band-has-always-been-a-brotherhood/ |title=Singer AJay Popoff on Lit: 'This Band Has Always Been a Brotherhood' |publisher=[[Loudwire|Loudwire.com]] |date=January 7, 2013 |accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> A video for \"Miss You Gone\" was released on June 13, 2013.\n\nOn December 9, 2013, the band announced via its [[Facebook]] page that it would perform a special 15th anniversary show for ''A Place in the Sun,'' where the band played the entire album from front to back on February 28, 2014, at the [[House of Blues]] in [[Anaheim, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lit|url=http://www.facebook.com/LitLounge|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''These Are the Days'' (2016\u2013present)===\n\nOn October 1, 2015 the band announced that they had been working on new music at SoundStage in Nashville, TN.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lit Working On New Music|url = http://www.litband.com/news/10-01-15/lit-working-new-music|website = www.litband.com|accessdate = November 18, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151118223959/http://www.litband.com/news/10-01-15/lit-working-new-music|archive-date = November 18, 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2016, Nathan Walker left the band to pursue other projects. The band brought in drummer Terry Stirling Jr. for the 2016 Summerland Tour. Evan Kilbourne replaced him the following year.\n\nOn October 26, 2016, Lit's music video for their new song \"Fast\" debuted on [[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]]. The band announced a [[PledgeMusic]] campaign for their new album on December 6, 2016. They also released another new song \"Back With You.\" These two songs show a shift in sound for the band to a more country-influenced sound.\n\nThe band released their sixth album, ''[[These Are the Days (Lit album)|These Are the Days]],'' on December 15, 2017.<ref>[http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/lit Lit: New Album! on PledgeMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\nOn the band's first album ''[[Tripping the Light Fantastic (album)|Tripping the Light Fantastic]]'', Lit incorporated elements of [[punk rock]], [[grunge]] and [[metal music|heavy metal]].<ref name=\"reviewone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tripping-the-light-fantastic-mw0000255837|title=Tripping the Light Fantastic - Lit|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2017-02-19}}</ref> The band moved away from the style featured on that album and moved to<ref name=\"reviewtwo\"/> a [[pop punk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/photos/20-pop-punk-albums-which-will-make-you-nostalgic/340824|title=20 Pop Punk Albums Which Will Make You Nostalgic|date=June 9, 2014|work=NME.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> and [[power pop]]<ref name=\"reviewtwo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-place-in-the-sun-mw0000049366|title=A Place in the Sun - Lit|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2017-02-19}}</ref> style on their album ''[[A Place in the Sun (Lit album)|A Place in the Sun]]''. Lit has been mainly described as [[alternative rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://classicrock.teamrock.com/features/2014-09-26/the-ryder-cup-of-rock|title=The Ryder Cup Of Rock|work=Classic Rock|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/ladera-242816-taste-lit.html|title=Lit to perform at Taste of Ladera|work=The Orange County Register|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"reviewone\"/>  and [[pop punk]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypages.com/music/late-90s-early-00s-pop-punkemo-bands-ranked/421992044 |title=Late '90s & early '00s pop-punk/emo bands, ranked |work=[[City Pages]] |last=Boller |first=Jay |date=May 18, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard band bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/307560/lit/biography|title=Lit - Biography|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|work=Billboard.com|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/6957m5/this-lit-performance-of-my-own-worst-enemy-from-1999-is-a-glorious-slice-of-american-history |title= This Video of Lit Performing in 1999 Is an Important Cultural Artifact of a Forgotten Time |work=Noisey |last=Garland |first=Emma |date=April 27, 2016 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> Lit also has been described as [[post-grunge]].<ref name=\"Billboard band bio\"/> Lit moved to [[country music|country]] sound with the band's 2017 album ''[[These Are the Days (Lit album)|These Are the Days]]''.<ref>https://www.stereogum.com/1965652/lit-discuss-their-evolution-from-my-own-worst-enemy-to-country-music/franchises/tracking-down/</ref> Lit's influences include [[Iron Maiden]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[The Cars]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Weezer]], [[Metallica]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], and [[Boston (band)|Boston]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seymourduncan.com/blog/backstage-pass/jeremy-popoff-of-lit |title=Jeremy Popoff of Lit |publisher=Seymour Duncan |last1=King |first1=Kat |last2=Sharken |first2=Lisa |date=March 9, 2007 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeffpearlman.com/jeremy-popoff/ |title=Jeremy Popoff |last=Pearlman |first=Jeff |date=January 6, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/897196/Cultural-corner--Band-Lit-to-perform-at-the-metals-plaza.html |title= Cultural corner: Band Lit to perform at the 'metals' plaza |work=[[Deseret News]] |last=Iwasaki |first=Scott |date=February 21, 2002 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* Kevin Baldes \u2013 bass guitar, lead vocals <small>(1988\u20131989);</small> bass guitar, backing vocals <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Ajay Popoff \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(1988\u20131989);</small> lead vocals, percussion, acoustic guitar <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Jeremy Popoff \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(1989\u2013present);</small> keyboards <small>(1998)</small>\n* Ryan Gillmor \u2013 guitar, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2010\u20132012; 2013; touring guest 2015\u20132016; 2016\u2013present)</small>\n* Evan Kilbourne \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Touring substitutes'''\n* [[Adrian Young]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2008)</small>\n* Rich Redmond \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2008)</small><ref>Rich Redmond recorded drums on unreleased demos from ''The View from the Bottom''.</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Sean Holland \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(1988\u20131992)</small>\n* Charles Ward \u2013 lead vocals <small>(1988\u20131989)</small>\n* [[Allen Shellenberger]] \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals <small>(1989\u20132009)</small>\n* Chadd Anthony (Chad Benekos) \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(1992\u20131995)</small>\n* Nathan Walker \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(touring substitute 2008, 2009; 2009\u20132016)</small><ref>Nathan Walker was the drum tech of Lit from around 2004 until around 2009, and filled-in for Allen while he was ill in 2008 and in 2009.</ref>\n*Terry Stirling Jr. \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2016\u20132017)</small>\n\n'''Touring guests'''\n* [[Stan Frazier (musician)|Stan Frazier]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2008)</small>\n* Jay Sparring \u2013 guitar <small>(2013)</small>\n* ???? \u2013 guitar, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2017)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lit discography}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Tripping the Light Fantastic (album)|Tripping the Light Fantastic]]'' <small>(1997)</small>\n* ''[[A Place in the Sun (Lit album)|A Place in the Sun]]'' <small>(1999)</small>\n* ''[[Atomic (Lit album)|Atomic]]'' <small>(2001)</small>\n* ''[[Lit (album)|Lit]]'' <small>(2004)</small>\n* ''[[The View from the Bottom]]'' <small>(2012)</small>\n* ''[[These Are the Days (Lit album)|These Are the Days]]'' <small>(2017)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://litband.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/LitTV LitTV at YouTube.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061022025055/http://www.pokerpages.com/articles/archives/chris-line03.htm Interview with Jeremy Popoff]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100920035113/http://www.citynetmagazine.com/entertainment/music/allen-shellenberger.html Interview with Allen Shellenberger]\n* {{IMDb name|id=1532264|name=Lit}}\n\n{{Lit (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:American post-grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:American pop rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Pop punk groups from California]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Lit\n| background = group_or_band\n| image = Lit band.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Lit performing at [[Mohegan Sun]] in [[Connecticut]] in 2005.\n| alias = Razzle <small>(1988\u20131994)</small> {{nowrap|Stain <small>(1994\u20131996)</small>}}\n| origin = [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], [[California]]<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\">{{cite book\n| first= Martin C.\n| last= Strong\n| year= 2000\n| title= The Great Rock Discography\n| edition= 5th\n| publisher= Mojo Books\n| location= Edinburgh\n| page= 575\n| isbn= 1-84195-017-3}}</ref>\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop punk]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\ncountry rock\n}}\n| years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n* [[DRT Entertainment|DRT]]\n* [[Megaforce Records|Megaforce]]\n}}\n| website = {{url|litband.com}}\n| current_members = Kevin Baldes<br>A. Jay Popoff<br>Jeremy Popoff<br>Ryan Gillmor<br> Evan Kilbourne\n| past_members = Sean Holland<br>Charles Ward<br>[[Allen Shellenberger]]<br>Chadd Anthony (Chad Benekos)<br>Nathan Walker<br>Terry Stirling Jr.\n}}\n\n'''Lit''' is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band, formed in 1988 in [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], [[California]]. They are best known for their song \"[[My Own Worst Enemy (song)|My Own Worst Enemy]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/lit-mn0000837886/biography|title=Lit - Biography|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|work=AllMusic|accessdate= March 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Pre-Lit (1986\u20131995)===\nJeremy Popoff and bassist Kevin Baldes met in 1986, and soon after, began playing music together. In 1987, Jeremy Popoff and Jerry Neel formed the band Strate Lace and performed three live shows together: The Troubador in Hollywood, The Waters Club in San Pedro, and a back-to-school party in a friend's back yard. Neel quit the band to pursue a career in the mortgage industry.\n\nLater on, high school friends Baldes (15 or 16 at the time) and Popoff's brother A. Jay (14 at the time) formed the pop metal band Razzle in 1988 with Sean Holland. The lineup included Kevin Baldes (bass, vocals), A. Jay Popoff (drums, percussion), Sean Holland (guitar), and Charles Ward (vocals). They performed their first show on June 26, 1988, at [[The Troubadour, West Hollywood|The Troubadour]]. In 1989, A. Jay switched from drums to lead vocals, and the band added guitarist Jeremy Popoff and drummer [[Allen Shellenberger]]. Things began to come together in 1990, when the group released a demo tape and an EP entitled ''New Vibe Revolution'' in 1993.  Razzle dissolved in 1993 and became Stain in 1994, which had a much harder and heavier sound. They released a demo tape in 1995 and eventually signed with Malicious Vinyl in 1995. After finding out the name \"Stain\" was already owned, the band changed their name to Lit.\n\n===''Tripping the Light Fantastic'' (1996\u20131997)===\nOn April 1, 1997 the group released ''[[Tripping the Light Fantastic (album)|Tripping the Light Fantastic]]'' on the Malicious Vinyl [[record label]].<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> Malicious Vinyl went out of business shortly after ''Tripping the Light Fantastic'' was released, which left the band unsigned once again. They spent their time writing a new batch of songs and showcasing for various record labels until they signed with [[RCA Records]] in 1998.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/>\n\n===The RCA years (1998\u20132002)===\nThe group gained popularity with their second album ''[[A Place in the Sun (Lit album)|A Place in the Sun]]'', released in February 1999. ''A Place in the Sun'' yielded the [[hit single]], \"[[My Own Worst Enemy (Lit song)|My Own Worst Enemy]],\" which peaked at number 51 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]], topping the [[Modern Rock Tracks|Billboard Hot Modern Rock Tracks]] chart for a total of 12 weeks, and receiving a ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Music Award for the biggest modern rock song of 1999. It was followed by \"[[Zip-Lock (song)|Zip-Lock]]\" (which featured [[Blink-182]] in the [[music video|video]]) and \"[[Miserable (song)|Miserable]]\", the latter of which was among the top ten most played songs of 2000 and featured [[Pamela Anderson]] in the video, as a [[giantess]] who lets the band walk on different parts her body before eventually betraying and [[Vorarephilia|devouring]] them all. Shortly after, the album went [[music recording sales certification|platinum]] in the US and [[music recording sales certification|gold]] in Canada, becoming the band's best selling album. The band performed over 286 shows and toured worldwide in support of ''A Place in the Sun''. In addition to the [[Vans Warped Tour]] and a slot on [[Woodstock 1999]], the band toured with [[The Offspring]], [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]], and [[No Doubt]]. The band's tracks also appeared in soundtracks of ''[[Ready to Rumble]]'' and ''[[The Replacements (film)|The Replacements]]''.\n\nLit followed up ''A Place in the Sun'' with the 2001 release of ''[[Atomic (Lit album)|Atomic]]''. The new album steered away from the sound of their last [[pop punk]] album, resulting in a more mature yet ultimately less successful format. The band's highest charting single was \"[[Lipstick and Bruises]]\" which reached [[Top 40|Top 10]] on the [[Modern Rock Tracks|Billboard's Hot Modern Rock Tracks]]. Lit toured to support ''Atomic'' with [[Kid Rock]] and [[Butch Walker]]. The group was released from their contract with RCA Records in late 2002.\n\n===Self-titled album (2003\u20132007)===\nLit went on a small, intimate club tour in the fall of 2003 before releasing the self-titled ''Lit'' on the [[DRT Entertainment]] label on June 24, 2004. The single \"Looks Like They Were Right\" made it on the Top 40 charts. That year the group also put out its first long-form [[DVD]], ''All Access'', on November 16, 2004.\n\n===Death of Allen Shellenberger===\n\nOn May 5, 2008, Lit announced that their drummer Allen Shellenberger was diagnosed with a brain tumor. Shellenberger immediately underwent clinical trials, chemotherapy and radiation at the Cedars-Sinai Maxine Dunitz Neurosurgical Institute. It was discovered that the tumor was [[malignant glioma]] and was incurable. His treatments were documented in a piece on [[ABC World News Tonight]] that aired in the same month. Lit cancelled their scheduled tour dates with [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] due to Shellenberger's diagnosis. On July 26, 2008, Lit held a benefit concert for Allen at the [[House Of Blues]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. A number of bands performed including [[Sugar Ray]] and [[Handsome Devil (band)|Handsome Devil]]. [[No Doubt]] drummer [[Adrian Young]] filled in for Shellenberger for a couple of songs. Both drummers also played at the same time for a few songs. The concert was Allen's last show with Lit, as he died at the age of 39 from his tumor on August 13, 2009.<ref name=\"consequenceofsound.net\">{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2009/08/14/lit-drummer-allen-shellenberger-dead-at-39/|title=Lit drummer Allen Shellenberger dead at 39|accessdate=August 14, 2009|publisher=Consequenceofsound.net}}</ref>\n\n===''The View from the Bottom'' (2009\u20132015)===\nOn November 23, 2009, Lit played their first concert since Allen Shellenberger's death. Drum tech Nathan Walker, who had filled in for Shellenberger earlier that year, was now his successor on drums. They later announced that they had begun to work on a new album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=3954749&blogId=520152622 |title=Lit Update - 11/27/09 van Lit op Myspace |publisher=Blogs.myspace.com |date=November 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065936/http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view |archivedate=February 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010 during an interview with OC Talk Radio, Lit hinted that they would return to a major label for their next release. They also revealed their work on a new management deal, as well as performing new material live.\n\nIn September 2010, Kevin Baldes confirmed that Lit were in the studio, writing and recording their sixth studio album. The band worked with producer [[Marti Frederiksen]] ([[Aerosmith]], [[Def Leppard]], [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Faith Hill]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=3954749&blogId=539381684 |title=Featured Content on Myspace |publisher=Blogs.myspace.com |accessdate=April 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065936/http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view |archivedate=February 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe band reported that they were still in the studio recording in July 2011, and released a demo video titled \"You Tonight\". Lit announced in December 2011 that they were back in the studio with producer [[Butch Walker]] to finish their new album. It was also announced that the band had signed with [[Megaforce Records]] and would release their new album ''[[The View from the Bottom]]'' on June 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chinashopmag.com/2012/01/lit-teams-up-with-butch-walker/ |title=Lit Teams Up With Butch Walker: This is How Awesome is Made &#124; ChinaShop |publisher=Chinashopmag.com |date=January 2, 2012 |accessdate=April 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723231138/http://www.chinashopmag.com/2012/01/lit-teams-up-with-butch-walker/ |archive-date=July 23, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe first single, \"You Tonight,\" was released on iTunes on May 1, 2012, and a video for \"The Broken\" was released in August 2012.\n\nOn January 7, 2013, frontman A. Jay Popoff told ''[[Loudwire]]'' that after Lit finished touring in support of ''The View from the Bottom'', they would begin writing their next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/a-jay-popoff-lit-this-band-has-always-been-a-brotherhood/ |title=Singer AJay Popoff on Lit: 'This Band Has Always Been a Brotherhood' |publisher=[[Loudwire|Loudwire.com]] |date=January 7, 2013 |accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> A video for \"Miss You Gone\" was released on June 13, 2013.\n\nOn December 9, 2013, the band announced via its [[Facebook]] page that it would perform a special 15th anniversary show for ''A Place in the Sun,'' where the band played the entire album from front to back on February 28, 2014, at the [[House of Blues]] in [[Anaheim, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lit|url=http://www.facebook.com/LitLounge|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''These Are the Days'' (2016\u2013present)===\n\nOn October 1, 2015 the band announced that they had been working on new music at SoundStage in Nashville, TN.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lit Working On New Music|url = http://www.litband.com/news/10-01-15/lit-working-new-music|website = www.litband.com|accessdate = November 18, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151118223959/http://www.litband.com/news/10-01-15/lit-working-new-music|archive-date = November 18, 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2016, Nathan Walker left the band to pursue other projects. The band brought in drummer Terry Stirling Jr. for the 2016 Summerland Tour. Evan Kilbourne replaced him the following year.\n\nOn October 26, 2016, Lit's music video for their new song \"Fast\" debuted on [[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]]. The band announced a [[PledgeMusic]] campaign for their new album on December 6, 2016. They also released another new song \"Back With You.\" These two songs show a shift in sound for the band to a more country-influenced sound.\n\nThe band released their sixth album, ''[[These Are the Days (Lit album)|These Are the Days]],'' on December 15, 2017.<ref>[http://www.pledgemusic.com/projects/lit Lit: New Album! on PledgeMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\nOn the band's first album ''[[Tripping the Light Fantastic (album)|Tripping the Light Fantastic]]'', Lit incorporated elements of [[punk rock]], [[grunge]] and [[metal music|heavy metal]].<ref name=\"reviewone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tripping-the-light-fantastic-mw0000255837|title=Tripping the Light Fantastic - Lit|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2017-02-19}}</ref> The band moved away from the style featured on that album and moved to<ref name=\"reviewtwo\"/> a [[pop punk]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/photos/20-pop-punk-albums-which-will-make-you-nostalgic/340824|title=20 Pop Punk Albums Which Will Make You Nostalgic|date=June 9, 2014|work=NME.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> and [[power pop]]<ref name=\"reviewtwo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-place-in-the-sun-mw0000049366|title=A Place in the Sun - Lit|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2017-02-19}}</ref> style on their album ''[[A Place in the Sun (Lit album)|A Place in the Sun]]''. Lit has been mainly described as [[alternative rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://classicrock.teamrock.com/features/2014-09-26/the-ryder-cup-of-rock|title=The Ryder Cup Of Rock|work=Classic Rock|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/ladera-242816-taste-lit.html|title=Lit to perform at Taste of Ladera|work=The Orange County Register|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"reviewone\"/>  and [[pop punk]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypages.com/music/late-90s-early-00s-pop-punkemo-bands-ranked/421992044 |title=Late '90s & early '00s pop-punk/emo bands, ranked |work=[[City Pages]] |last=Boller |first=Jay |date=May 18, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard band bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/307560/lit/biography|title=Lit - Biography|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|work=Billboard.com|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/6957m5/this-lit-performance-of-my-own-worst-enemy-from-1999-is-a-glorious-slice-of-american-history |title= This Video of Lit Performing in 1999 Is an Important Cultural Artifact of a Forgotten Time |work=Noisey |last=Garland |first=Emma |date=April 27, 2016 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> Lit also has been described as [[post-grunge]].<ref name=\"Billboard band bio\"/> Lit moved to [[country music|country]] sound with the band's 2017 album ''[[These Are the Days (Lit album)|These Are the Days]]''.<ref>https://www.stereogum.com/1965652/lit-discuss-their-evolution-from-my-own-worst-enemy-to-country-music/franchises/tracking-down/</ref> Lit's influences include [[Iron Maiden]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[The Cars]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Weezer]], [[Metallica]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], and [[Boston (band)|Boston]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seymourduncan.com/blog/backstage-pass/jeremy-popoff-of-lit |title=Jeremy Popoff of Lit |publisher=Seymour Duncan |last1=King |first1=Kat |last2=Sharken |first2=Lisa |date=March 9, 2007 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeffpearlman.com/jeremy-popoff/ |title=Jeremy Popoff |last=Pearlman |first=Jeff |date=January 6, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/897196/Cultural-corner--Band-Lit-to-perform-at-the-metals-plaza.html |title= Cultural corner: Band Lit to perform at the 'metals' plaza |work=[[Deseret News]] |last=Iwasaki |first=Scott |date=February 21, 2002 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* Kevin Baldes \u2013 bass guitar, lead vocals <small>(1988\u20131989);</small> bass guitar, backing vocals <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* A. Jay Popoff \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(1988\u20131989);</small> lead vocals, percussion, acoustic guitar <small>(1989\u2013present)</small>\n* Jeremy Popoff \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(1989\u2013present);</small> keyboards <small>(1998)</small>\n* Ryan Gillmor \u2013 guitar, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2010\u20132012; 2013; touring guest 2015\u20132016; 2016\u2013present)</small>\n* Evan Kilbourne \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Touring substitutes'''\n* [[Adrian Young]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2008)</small>\n* Rich Redmond \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2008)</small><ref>Rich Redmond recorded drums on unreleased demos from ''The View from the Bottom''.</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Sean Holland \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(1988\u20131992)</small>\n* Charles Ward \u2013 lead vocals <small>(1988\u20131989)</small>\n* [[Allen Shellenberger]] \u2013 drums, percussion, backing vocals <small>(1989\u20132009)</small>\n* Chadd Anthony (Chad Benekos) \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(1992\u20131995)</small>\n* Nathan Walker \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(touring substitute 2008, 2009; 2009\u20132016)</small><ref>Nathan Walker was the drum tech of Lit from around 2004 until around 2009, and filled-in for Allen while he was ill in 2008 and in 2009.</ref>\n*Terry Stirling Jr. \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2016\u20132017)</small>\n\n'''Touring guests'''\n* [[Stan Frazier (musician)|Stan Frazier]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(2008)</small>\n* Jay Sparring \u2013 guitar <small>(2013)</small>\n* ???? \u2013 guitar, keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2017)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lit discography}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Tripping the Light Fantastic (album)|Tripping the Light Fantastic]]'' <small>(1997)</small>\n* ''[[A Place in the Sun (Lit album)|A Place in the Sun]]'' <small>(1999)</small>\n* ''[[Atomic (Lit album)|Atomic]]'' <small>(2001)</small>\n* ''[[Lit (album)|Lit]]'' <small>(2004)</small>\n* ''[[The View from the Bottom]]'' <small>(2012)</small>\n* ''[[These Are the Days (Lit album)|These Are the Days]]'' <small>(2017)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://litband.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/LitTV LitTV at YouTube.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061022025055/http://www.pokerpages.com/articles/archives/chris-line03.htm Interview with Jeremy Popoff]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100920035113/http://www.citynetmagazine.com/entertainment/music/allen-shellenberger.html Interview with Allen Shellenberger]\n* {{IMDb name|id=1532264|name=Lit}}\n\n{{Lit (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:American post-grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:American pop rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Pop punk groups from California]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "MikMarie", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated the page to fix spelling errors of Ajay's name.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lit_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Debra Granik", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Debra Granik\n| image = Debra Granik.jpg\n| alt = Granik at the 2010 Deauville American Film Festival\n| caption = Granik at the 2010 [[Deauville&nbsp;American&nbsp;Film&nbsp;Festival]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|02|06}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] U.S.}}\n| education = [[Brandeis University]]<br/>[[Tisch School of the Arts]]\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n*Film director\n*screenwriter}}\n| years_active = 1987\u2013present\n| spouse = Jonathan Scheuer\n| children = 1\n}}\n'''Debra Granik''' (born February 6, 1963) is an American filmmaker.<ref name=RafaelPiRoman-WintersBone-2011>{{cite news|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|last2=Roman|first2=Rafael Pi|title=Sunday Arts Profile: Debra Granik Interview with Rafael Pi Roman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9SiTYdsqpY|work=Rafael Pi Roman|date=17 February 2011|format=Video interview}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-StrayDog-2014>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Kate|title=Download: Debra Granik|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/opinion/sunday/debra-granik.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1 November 2014|language=en}}</ref> She is most known for 2004's ''[[Down to the Bone (film)|Down to the Bone]],'' which starred [[Vera Farmiga]], 2010's ''[[Winter's Bone]],'' which starred [[Jennifer Lawrence]] in her breakout performance and for which Granik was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]],<ref name=VanityFair-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Sperling|first1=Nicole|title=The Filmmaker Who Directed Jennifer Lawrence's First Oscar-Nominated Role Has a New Star in Leave No Trace|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/06/debra-granik-jennifer-lawrence-thomasin-mckenzie-leave-no-trace|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=26 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> and 2018's ''[[Leave No Trace (film)|Leave No Trace]],'' a film based on the book ''My Abandonment'' by [[Peter Rock (novelist)|Peter Rock]].<ref name=Vulture-Sundance-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Buchanan|first1=Kyle|title=After Launching Jennifer Lawrence, Director Debra Granik Is Finally Back|url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/06/winters-bone-director-debra-granik-on-leave-no-trace.html|work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=27 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nGranik was born in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], to father William R. Granik, who was an attorney with [[U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development|H.U.D.]] who litigated [[fair housing]],<ref name=NYTimes-Father-HUD-1989>{{cite news|last1=Lewin|first1=Tamar|title=Children as Neighbors? Elderly Are Worried|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/11/28/us/children-as-neighbors-elderly-are-worried.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 November 1989|language=en}}</ref> and mother Brenda Granik Zusman.<ref name=WashPost-WilliamGranik-Obit-2012>{{cite news|title=William R. Granik: Notice|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/washingtonpost/obituary.aspx?fhid=10909&n=william-r-granik&pid=156052506|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> She grew up in the suburbs of [[Washington D.C.]]<ref name=HReporter-LeaveNoTrace-Interview-2018>{{cite news|last1=Kilkenny|first1=Katie|title=Director Debra Granik Explains Why It's Been Eight Long Years Between 'Winter's Bone' and Her New Film|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/director-debra-granik-explains-why-been-eight-long-years-between-winters-bone-leave-no-trace-1123551|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=29 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> Her parents divorced in 1978. \n\nGranik is the granddaughter of broadcast pioneer Ted Granik (1907\u20131970),<ref name=LC-TheodoreGranikPapers-2013>{{cite book|last1=Sullivan|first1=Joseph|last2=Miller|first2=Mike|last3=Kerwin|first3=Patrick|last4=Monagle|first4=John|title=Theodore Granik Papers (1930-1970): A Finding Aid to the Collection in the Library of Congress \u2013 MSS75822|date=2013|publisher=Manuscript Division, Library of Congress |location=Washington, D.C.|url=http://findingaids.loc.gov/exist_collections/service/mss/eadxmlmss/eadpdfmss/2013/ms013088.pdf|format=Finding aid}}</ref> founder and moderator of the long-run public affairs panel discussion program, ''[[The American Forum of the Air]],'' on from 1934 to 1956, first on the radio and later on television.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Ella|title=Debra Granik Explores the Ozarks in 'Winter's Bone'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/movies/02granik.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 April 2010|language=en}}</ref> Granik is from a [[Jewish]] family.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012>{{cite news|last1=Shebar|first1=Billy|title=Skateboarding on Hardscrabble|url=http://www.brandeis.edu/magazine/2012/summer/featured-stories/granik.html|work=Brandeis Magazine|publisher=[[Brandeis University]]|date=Summer 2012|language=en}}</ref><ref name=JewishJournal-WintersBone-Interview-2011>{{cite news|last1=Pfefferman|first1=Naomi|title=Debra Granik cuts to the emotional bone with 'Winter's Bone'|url=http://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts/89357/|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|date=18 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Granik received her B.A. in political science from [[Brandeis University]].<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=Brandeis-EnvironmentalProtection-Thesis-1984>{{cite book|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|title=Environmental Protection: A Citizens' Movement|date=1984|publisher=Brandeis University|location=Waltham, MA|url=https://search.library.brandeis.edu/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=BRAND_ALMA21206021730001921&context=L&vid=BRAND&search_scope=ALMA&tab=alma&lang=en_US|language=en|format=Senior honors thesis/dissertation|oclc=31927747}}</ref> As an undergraduate at Brandeis, Granik also took classes at the [[Studio for Interrelated Media]] at the [[Massachusetts College of Art]].<ref name=NYU-Alumni-Bio-2018 /> In 2001, Granik received an MFA from [[New York University|NYU's]] [[Tisch School of the Arts]].<ref name=NYU-SundancePremieres-2018>{{cite news|title=Features: 2018 Sundance Premieres|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/alumni/tisch-at-sundance/2018-sundance/premieres|work=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|publisher=[[New York University]]|date=2018|language=en|quote=Debra Granik '01 (MFA, Film), director/writer}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nWhile at Brandeis, Granik took Henry Felt's film and media workshop production class and volunteered with the Boston grassroots filmmaking organization Women's Video Collective.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=DP30-WintersBone-Interview-2011>{{cite news|last1=Poland|first1=David|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=DP/30: Winter's Bone, co-writer/director Debra Granik|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qbgKUW6cWQ8|work=DP/30: The Oral History Of Hollywood|date=4 September 2011|format=Video interview}}</ref> She also took film classes at the [[Studio for Interrelated Media]] at the [[Massachusetts College of Art]].<ref name=NYU-Alumni-Bio-2018 /> During this time, Granik made educational films for trade unions on subjects like workplace health and safety, one of which was made for the Massachusetts Division of Occupational Safety.<ref name=PreventingCumulativeTraumaDisorders-1990>{{cite film|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|title=It Didn't Have to Happen: Preventing Cumulative Trauma Disorders|date=1990|publisher=Massachusetts Dept. of Industrial Accidents, Office of Safety|location=Boston|type=VHS video|oclc=53200528}}</ref> Granik worked in production on educational media projects, eventually working on long form documentaries by Boston-area filmmakers before deciding to go to graduate school for filmmaking at [[New York University]].<ref name=NYU-Alumni-Bio-2018>{{cite news|title=Graduate Film: Alumni: Debra Granik|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/grad-film/alumni/debra-granik-|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|publisher=[[New York University]]|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Granik directed her first short film, ''Snake Feed,'' as her senior thesis with the mentorship of NYU film professor [[Boris Frumin]], who was instrumental in sharing his love of post-World War II European [[neorealist film]]s.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /><ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=DP30-WintersBone-Interview-2011 /> ''Snake Feed,'' which began its life as a 7-minute documentary portrait exercise, was accepted into [[Sundance Institute]]'s Lab Program for screenwriting and directing.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /> Granik workshopped and developed the short film into a feature film at the Sundance Lab.<ref name=PBS-Reel13-DownToTheBone-2010>{{cite news|last1=Pe\u00f1a|first1=Richard|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=Interview: Debra Granik, Director|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/reel-13-interview-debra-granik-director/|work=Reel 13|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting System|PBS]]|date=1 September 2010|format=Video interview}}</ref> Granik has said that ''Snake Feed'' was a work of narrative fiction, with the main characters, recovering addict Irene and her boyfriend Rick, playing dramatized versions of themselves.<ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005>{{cite news|last1=Kipp|first1=Jeremiah|title=Cutting Close to the Bone: An interview with Down To The Bone writer-director Debra Granik|url=https://www.filmmakermagazine.com/archives/online_features/cutting_close.php|work=[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]|date=21 November 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060413142519/https://www.filmmakermagazine.com/archives/online_features/cutting_close.php|archivedate=13 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the short film of ''Snake Feed'' and the story of Irene and Rick became the basis of Granik's first feature-length film, ''[[Down to the Bone (film)|Down to the Bone]],'' which was a fictionalized depiction of their struggles.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /><ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005 /> ''Down to the Bone'' is the story of an upstate New York mother who goes to rehab to kick her cocaine addiction and ends up falling in love with a nurse and descending back into her old drug habits.<ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005 /><ref name=SouthernSpaces-WintersBone-Review-2010>{{cite journal|last1=Moon|first1=Michael|last2=Talley|first2=Colin|title=Life in a Shatter Zone: Debra Granik's Film Winter's Bone|journal=[[Southern Spaces]]|date=2010|volume=6 December 2010|doi=10.18737/M73K6M|url=https://southernspaces.org/2010/life-shatter-zone-debra-graniks-film-winters-bone|language=en|issn=1551-2754}}</ref> ''Down to the Bone'' was based on an original screenplay written by Granik and her creative partner, [[Anne Rosellini]].<ref name=PBS-Reel13-DownToTheBone-2010 /><ref name=NYTimes-DownToTheBone-Review-2005>{{cite news|last1=Stevens|first1=Dana|title=Film in Review; Down to the Bone|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/25/arts/movies/film-in-review-down-to-the-bone.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=25 November 2005|language=en}}</ref> The role of the main character Irene, played by [[Vera Farmiga]], significantly raised Farmiga's profile as an actor.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /><ref name=NYTimesMag-DownToTheBone-Farmiga-2006>{{cite news|last1=Hirschberg|first1=Lynn|title=A Film of One's Own|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/03/magazine/03actesses.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 September 2006|language=en}}</ref> ''Down to the Bone'' was shot in [[Ulster County, New York|Ulster County]] in upstate [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=RafaelPiRoman-WintersBone-2011 />\n\nGranik's second feature, 2010's ''[[Winter's Bone]]'', was an adaptation by Granik and Rosellini of the 2006 novel by [[Daniel Woodrell]].<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Review-2010>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=A. O.|title=Jennifer Lawrence in Debra Granik's Bleak Ozarks Film|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/11/movies/11winter.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=10 June 2010|language=en}}</ref> It is the story of Ree Dolly, a teenager living in the [[The Ozarks|Missouri's Ozark Mountains]] who is the sole caretaker of her two younger siblings and her catatonic mother. She is forced to hunt down her missing drug-dealing father in order to save her family from eviction.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 />\n\nThe film starred a then-unknown [[Jennifer Lawrence]] and [[John Hawkes (actor)|John Hawkes]] and won the Grand Jury Prize: Dramatic Film at the [[2010 Sundance Film Festival]], which led to a distribution deal with [[Roadside Attractions]].<ref name=IndieWire-WintersBone-Review-2010>{{cite news|last1=Kohn|first1=Eric|title=Review: Drama in Absence: Debra Granik's \"Winter's Bone\"|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2010/06/review-drama-in-absence-debra-graniks-winters-bone-245347/|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=7 June 2010}}</ref> ''Winter's Bone'' won the [[Seattle International Film Festival]] Golden Space Needle Audience Award for Best Director and Best Actress award for Jennifer Lawrence.<ref name=Seattlest-WintersBone-Interview-2010>{{cite news|last1=Mikel|first1=Amy|title=An Interview with Debra Granik, Director of Winter's Bone|url=http://seattlest.com/2010/07/01/an_interview_with_debra_granik_dire.php|work=Seattlest|publisher=[[Gothamist]]|date=1 July 2010}}</ref> In 2011, ''Winter's Bone'' was nominated for four [[83rd Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Jennifer Lawrence and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for John Hawkes.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Oscars-2011>{{cite news|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|title=The Carpetbagger: A Magical Morning in New York|url=https://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/25/a-magical-morning-in-new-york/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=25 January 2011|language=en}}</ref> The film featured a soundtrack made up of old time gospel, bluegrass, and traditional music found in the Ozarks and was produced by Steve Peters. It features the singing of Marideth Sisco, who worked as a music and folklore consultant for the region, and also appeared in the ''Winter's Bone.'' The actor [[John Hawkes (actor)|John Hawkes]] sings one track on the soundtrack.<ref name=LargeheartedBoy-WintersBoneSoundtrack-2010>{{cite news|last1=Peters|first1=Steve|title=Largehearted Boy: Soundtracked \u2013 \"Winter's Bone\" by Steve Peters|url=http://www.largeheartedboy.com/blog/archive/2010/12/soundtracked_wi.html|work=Largehearted Boy|date=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Winter's Bone'' was shot on location in the [[Ozark]] area of southern [[Missouri]]. Granik cast many of the supporting roles with first-time actors from the surrounding area and all of the homes on screen were established Ozark homes\u2014no sets were built for this film.<ref name=Seattlest-WintersBone-Interview-2010 /><ref name=AVClub-WintersBone-Interview-2010>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Sam|title=Interview: Debra Granik|url=https://film.avclub.com/debra-granik-1798220605|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=24 June 2010}}</ref> For the look of the film, Granik kept most of the established aesthetics of the homes in which they were shooting and many of the few mementos that were added to the homes were contributed by Ozark people in the community.<ref name=SouthernSpaces-WintersBone-Review-2010 />\n\nGranik produced and directed an [[HBO]] television pilot called ''American High Life.'' The show was a family drama that \"follows a young career woman to her economically depressed small home town in the midwest.\"<ref name=IndieWire-AmHighLife-2012>{{cite news|first1=Anne|last1=Thompson|title=Exclusive: 'Winter's Bone' Director Debra Granik's Next Projects: HBO Series, Doc, Another 'Bone' Movie with Russell Banks|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/whats-next-for-winters-bone-director-debra-granik-hbo-doc-another-bone-movie-with-russell-banks|date=4 May 2012|work=[[IndieWire]]}}</ref> The show was not picked up.<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Matthew|title=Debra Granik Is The Hollywood Director Who Casts Nobodies To Capture Real Rural America|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/debra-granik-leave-no-trace_us_5b34e24be4b0b5e692f554b4|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nGranik developed a film adaption of ''[[Rule of the Bone]]'', the 1995 novel by [[Russell Banks]], but the project is still in development.<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018 />\n\nIn 2014, Granik's film, ''Stray Dog,'' was released.<ref name=NYTimes-StrayDog-Review-2015>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=A.O.|title=Review: 'Stray Dog' Documents a Complex Veteran|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/movies/review-stray-dog-documents-a-complex-veteran.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 July 2015|language=en}}</ref> The film is a documentary about a man named Ron Hall, whose nickname is \"Stray Dog,\" and portrays his life as an avid biker and Vietnam Veteran who sometimes struggles with PTSD.<ref name=LATimes-StrayDog-2014>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Amy|title=Debra Granik tells a Vietnam veteran's tale in 'Stray Dog' documentary|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-debra-granik-stray-dog-20140618-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=18 June 2014}}</ref> The film documents Hall's participation in an annual pilgrimage motorcycle ride called \"Ride to the Wall\" with fellow biker Vietnam vets from all over the country where they ride to the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /> Granik had met Hall, who had a small role on ''Winter's Bone,'' during filming.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=NYTimes-StrayDog-Review-2015 />\n\nGranik directed the drama ''[[Leave No Trace (film)|Leave No Trace]]'', starring [[Ben Foster]] and newcomer [[Thomasin McKenzie]], which was released in 2018, domestically by [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]] and internationally by Sony Worldwide Acquisitions.<ref name=HReporter-LeaveNoTrace-Interview-2018 /><ref name=NYU-SundanceDistro-2018>{{cite news|title=Grad Film Shines at Sundance|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/grad-film/news/2018/grad-film-shines-at-sundance|work=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|publisher=[[New York University]]|date=2018|language=en}}</ref> The film tells the story of a father and daughter who illegally live on government land and are forced to adapt to more traditional living in mainstream life.<ref name=Vulture-Sundance-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=LATimes-LeaveNoTrace-Feature-2018>{{cite news|last1=Olsen|first1=Mark|title=Filmmaker Debra Granik returns with drama of family and survival in 'Leave No Trace'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-sundance-debra-granik-leave-no-trace-20180123-htmlstory.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=23 January 2018}}</ref> It examines ideas of self-reliance and community, and was a critics' pick of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=NYTimes-LeaveNoTrace-Review-2018>{{cite news|last1=Dargis|first1=Manohla|title=Review: 'Leave No Trace' Is a Very American Story About Survival|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/movies/leave-no-trace-review-ben-foster.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> ''Leave No Trace'' premiered at the 2018 [[Sundance Film Festival]], and played at the [[Cannes Film Festival]], and was shot in the forested areas of [[Oregon]], including [[Forest Park (Portland, Oregon)|Forest Park]] near [[Portland, Oregon]], over the course of 30 days.<ref name=VanityFair-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=AP-LeaveNoTrace-Cannes-2018>{{cite news|last1=Coyle|first1=Jake|title=In 'Leave No Trace,' Debra Granik stays off the beaten path|url=https://apnews.com/58afc195ed7044459285d59bb06ae35b|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=25 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> In addition to Oregon, [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] was used for locations, with some scenes shot at a Christmas tree farm.<ref name=OPB-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Notarianni|first1=John|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title='Leave No Trace' Director Debra Granik On Shooting A True Oregon Film |url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/article/leave-no-trace-oregon-film-director-interview-debra-granik/|work=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|date=30 June 2018|language=en|format=Includes audio}}</ref> ''Leave No Trace'' took approximately three and a half years to develop, from the first time Granik read Peter Rock's novel, ''My Abandonment,'' on which the film was based.<ref name=BUILDseries-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ricky|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|last3=Rosellini|first3=Anne|last4=Reisman|first4=Linda|last5=Harrison|first5=Anne|title=Debra Granik, Anne Rosellini, Linda Reisman & Anne Harrison Discuss \"Leave No Trace\"|url=https://www.buildseries.com/video/5b3291ffbf48853c22c34717/|work=BUILD Series|date=26 June 2018|format=Video interview}}</ref>\n\nOther projects Granik has in development include a documentary about life after being released from jail and the subject of [[recidivism]] in East Baltimore \u2013 that was to feature [[Felicia Pearson|Felicia \"Snoop\" Pearson]] from ''[[The Wire]]'' and elements of her memoir, ''[[Grace After Midnight]]''<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /> \u2013 but is now a documentary about four former inmates in New York City.<ref name=ScreenDaily-NickelDimed-2018>{{cite news|last1=Kay|first1=Jeremy|title=Debra Granik's 'Nickel And Dimed' looks for partners at Cannes (exclusive)|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/debra-graniks-nickel-and-dimed-looks-for-partners-at-cannes-exclusive/5129144.article|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|date=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=FilmComment-FutureProjects-2018>{{cite journal|last1=Lizotte|first1=Chloe|title=News to Me: Debra Granik, Mia Hansen-L\u00f8ve, Claude Lanzmann|journal=[[Film Comment]]|date=9 July 2018|url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/news-debra-granik-mia-hansen-love-claude-lanzmann/}}</ref>\n\nAnother project is a film based on [[Barbara Ehrenreich]]'s book, ''[[Nickel and Dimed|Nickel and Dimed: On (Not) Getting By in America]],'' which focuses on poverty and the [[working poor]] in America.<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=FilmComment-FutureProjects-2018 />\n\n== Themes ==\nGranik is known for discovering actors like [[Jennifer Lawrence]]<ref name=AFI-WintersBone-Casting-2011>{{cite news|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|title=Winter's Bone Director/Co-Writer, Debra Granik on Casting the Film|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xoJj1b-GUYQ|work=[[American Film Institute]]|date=2 March 2011|format=Video interview}}</ref>, [[Vera Farmiga]] and [[Thomasin McKenzie]] who have gone on to successful careers after early roles in Granik's films. She is also known for using local, non-professional actors in her films.<ref name=VanityFair-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=PBS-Reel13-DownToTheBone-2010 /> Granik has worked with creative partner [[Anne Rosellini]] on all of her films.<ref name=BUILDseries-LeaveNoTrace-2018 />\n\nGranik has said that she sees a common thread of press coverage describing her as having a \"comeback narrative,\"<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /> along with questions about how much time has elapsed between projects,<ref name=BUILDseries-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /> partly due to the relatively low output of films in her career compared to the contemporaries she started out with.<ref name=Vulture-Sundance-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=LATimes-StrayDog-2014 />\n\nInterviewed by Jeremiah Kipp in ''[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]'' in 2005, Granik discussed the challenges of directing a move like ''Down to the Bone''. She gave an overview of the challenges involved in doing a film about addiction:\n:The traditional storyline in an American film is usually in the form of a V shape. I am oversimplifying, but we see someone tumbling down, they hit bottom, and then they rise up again and find redemption. Anyone who personally, tangentially or culturally knows anything about addiction is aware that it resembles an EKG. Up and down, up and down. Very few people ever get clean on the first or second attempt. For many people, it\u2019s something they have to try over and over again. You get knocked down and ask all the ethical questions like how many chances do you give a person? When is the last chance? How many chances do they get? Can you imagine how difficult it is to fit that in a feature-length film? But those are the questions that are worth asking... The reason why boils down to the word \u201cdark\u201d. It is the scariest four-letter word in American storytelling and in this culture. Our film had a strong reception in Europe and achieved distribution, but that was not the case here. We received so many responses like, \u201cWe love the film, but we cannot do anything with it or we\u2019ll lose our shirts. We\u2019re sorry.\u201d The intervention comes from people like Laemmle/Zeller Films. Every couple of years, some mavericks take on this challenge of distributing so-called un-distributable films. They take those films on a small run and allow them to see the light of day. Those efforts are what give a film like ''Down to the Bone'' a chance to have a life of some kind.<ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005 />\n\nGranik's films deal with issues of personal strength and willpower, like the character of Ree Dolly in ''[[Winter's Bone]]''. She cites [[Mike Leigh]], [[Ken Loach]], [[Shane Meadows]], the [[Dardenne brothers]], [[Laurent Cantet]], and [[Abbas Kiarostami]] as some of her major influences in her directing career.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 />In a 2018 interview with [https://ff2media.com/thehotpinkpen/ FF2 Media] about ''Leave No Trace'', Granik discusses the themes of the film and what drew her to creating the film:<blockquote>I realized while reading it that one of the turning points in a girl\u2019s coming-of-age is coming to terms with the fact that as much as you may care about someone, you can\u2019t necessarily save them or even help them. You can be loving and tolerant, but you can\u2019t fix them. And that\u2019s something she\u2019s really struggling with in a really robust way, especially when they\u2019re in a new setting. And I really liked the fact that Tom is the one thing that\u2019s grounding him. She is his source of meaning. His sense of self-worth is bolstered by being meaningful to her, by being her dad. He takes pride in being her teacher and taking responsibility for her. And I was just so interested in the universality of that. The ties that bind is core material. There\u2019s nothing new about those themes, but I really liked that the novel had renewed my interest in exploring them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ff2media.com/blog/2018/06/28/modern-prospero-and-miranda-in-debra-graniks-leave-no-trace/|title=Modern Prospero and Miranda in Debra Granik\u2019s \u2018Leave No Trace\u2019|last=Coffin|first=Lesley|date=2018-06-28|website=FF2 Media|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGranik is married to Jonathan Scheuer, who has executive produced her films and is Vice Chairman of the Board of Trustees of [[National Jazz Museum in Harlem]].<ref name=LargeheartedBoy-WintersBoneSoundtrack-2010 /><ref name=NatlJazzMuseumHarlem-Board-Scheuer-2018>{{cite news|title=Who We Are: Board of Trustees|url=http://jazzmuseuminharlem.org/about-us/who-we-are/|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=[[National Jazz Museum in Harlem]]|quote=Jonathan Scheuer, Vice Chairman}}</ref> They live in New York City and have a daughter.<ref name=LATimes-StrayDog-2014 />\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 1987: ''Two in Twenty'' (TV series) for Somerville Community Access Television \u2013 director/cinematographer<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 />\n* 1990: ''It Didn't Have to Happen: Preventing Cumulative Trauma Disorders'' (documentary) \u2013 producer<ref name=PreventingCumulativeTraumaDisorders-1990 />\n* 1997: ''Snake Feed'' (short film) \u2013 producer, writer, director, off-line editor\n* 1997; ''American Independents II: The Blinking Madonna and Other Miracles'' (short film) \u2013 conceived by<ref name=NYTimes-BlinkingMadonna-Review-1997>{{cite news|last1=James|first1=Caryn|title=Coming to Terms With Family Secrets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/12/arts/coming-to-terms-with-family-secrets.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 May 1997|language=en}}</ref>\n* 1998: ''Smear'' (short film) \u2013 boom operator\n* 1998: ''Jorge'' (short film) \u2013 assistant camera\n* 1998: ''99 Threadwaxing'' (short film) \u2013 cinematographer\n* 2002: ''Breaker'' (short film) \u2013 cinematographer\n* 2003: ''[[Thunder in Guyana]]'' (documentary) \u2013 cinematographer<ref name=PBS-IndependentLens-Guyana-2003>{{cite news|title=Thunder in Guyana: Film Credits|url=http://www.pbs.org/independentlens/thunderinguyana/credits.html|work=[[Independent Lens]]|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]|date=2003|quote=The Film: Filmmaker Suzanne Wasserman shot Thunder in Guayana between 1997 and 1999}}</ref>\n* 2004: ''[[Down to the Bone (film)|Down to the Bone]]'' \u2013 writer, director, additional photographer\n* 2005: ''[[Independent Lens]]: Thunder in Guyana/Unites States of Poetry'' \u2013 cinematographer<ref name=NYTimes-Guyana-Review-2005>{{cite news|last1=Heffernan|first1=Virginia|title=A Radical Journey From Chicago to Guyana|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/22/arts/television/a-radical-journey-from-chicago-to-guyana.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 February 2005|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''[[Winter's Bone]]'' \u2013 adapted screenplay, director\n* 2014: ''Stray Dog'' (documentary) \u2013 writer, director\n* 2015: ''[[Independent Lens]]: Stray Dog'' (documentary) \u2013 writer, director\n* 2018: ''[[Leave No Trace (film)|Leave No Trace]]'' \u2013 adapted screenplay, director\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n:{{see|List of accolades received by Winter's Bone}}\n* 1998: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[List of Sundance Film Festival award winners#1998|Honorable Mention Short Filmmaking]] for ''Snake Feed''<ref name=NYTimes-SnakeFeed-SundanceAward-1998>{{cite news|last1=Maslin|first1=Janet|title=Various Guises of Misery in Sundance Winners|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/26/movies/various-guises-of-misery-in-sundance-winners.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=26 January 1998|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2004: [[Deauville American Film Festival]], Grand Prix (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone''\n* 2004: [[Gotham Awards]], [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2010]], Breakthrough Director Award (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone''\n* 2004: [[Sundance Film Festival]], Grand Jury Prize Dramatic (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone''\n* 2004: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[List of Sundance Film Festival award winners#2004|Directing Award Dramatic]] for ''Down to the Bone''<ref name=NYTimes-DownToTheBone-Review-2005 />\n* 2005: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit John Cassavetes Award|John Cassavetes Award]] (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone'' \u2013 with Richard Lieske, Susan Leber, Anne Rosellini\n* 2010: [[Berlin International Film Festival]], [[International Confederation of Art Cinemas|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale des Cin\u00e9mas d\u2019Art et d\u2019Essai (C.I.C.A.E.)]], Forum Award for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2010: [[Berlin International Film Festival]], ''[[Tagesspiegel]],'' Readers' Jury Award for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2010: [[Deauville American Film Festival]], Prix du Jury for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 tied with ''[[The Myth of the American Sleepover]],'' directed by [[David Robert Mitchell]]\n* 2010: [[Deauville American Film Festival]], Grand Prix (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2010: [[Gotham Awards]], [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2010]], [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Feature|Best Feature]] for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini, Alix Madigan<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-GothamAwards-2010>{{cite news|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|title=The Carpetbagger: 'Winter's Bone' Dominates at Gothams|url=https://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/29/winters-bone-dominates-at-gothams/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=29 November 2010|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2010: [[Gotham Awards]], [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2010]], Audience Award (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini, Alix Madigan<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-GothamAwards-2010 />\n* 2010: [[Seattle International Film Festival]], Golden Space Needle Award, Best Director for ''Winter's Bone''<ref name=Seattlest-WintersBone-Interview-2010 />\n* 2010: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[List of Sundance Film Festival award winners#2010|Grand Jury Prize: Dramatic Film]] for ''Winter's Bone''<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-SundanceAwards-2010>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=The Carpetbagger: Sundance Spreads the Love|url=https://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/30/sundance-spreads-the-love/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 January 2010|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2010: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[Waldo Salt#The Waldo Salt Screenwriting Award|Waldo Salt Screenwriting Award]], for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-SundanceAwards-2010 />\n* 2011: [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], [[83rd Academy Awards]], [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Oscars-2011 />\n* 2011: [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], [[83rd Academy Awards]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini, based on the novel by [[Daniel Woodrell]]<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Oscars-2011 />\n* 2011: [[Athena Film Festival]], Director's Award for Vision and Talent for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[British Independent Film Awards]], Best Foreign Film (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[Humanitas Prize]], Sundance Film Category for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini<ref name=Humanitas-WintersBone-2011>{{cite news|title=Past Winners: 2011 Anne Rosellini & Debra Granik: Winter's Bone|url=https://www.humanitasprize.org/past-winners/|work=[[Humanitas Prize]]}}</ref>\n* 2011: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Film|Best Feature]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini\n* 2015: [[Atlanta Film Festival]], Jury Award, Best Documentary Feature for ''Stray Dog'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini\n* 2015: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[30th Independent Spirit Awards]] [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]] (nominated) for ''Stray Dog''\n* 2018: [[Seattle International Film Festival]], Grand Jury Prize (nominated) for ''Leave No Trace''\n* 2018: [[Seattle International Film Festival]], Golden Space Needle Award, Best Director (nominated) for ''Leave No Trace''\n* 2018: [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director]]\n* 2018: [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Independent Films]]\n* 2019: Inaugural Career Spotlight Award of the [[Boston Society of Film Critics]]<ref>https://bostonfilmcritics.org/blog/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite news|last1=Pe\u00f1a|first1=Richard|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=Interview: Debra Granik, Director|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/reel-13-interview-debra-granik-director/|work=Reel 13|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting System|PBS]]|date=1 September 2010|format=Video interview}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Poland|first1=David|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=DP/30: Winter's Bone, co-writer/director Debra Granik|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qbgKUW6cWQ8|work=DP/30: The Oral History Of Hollywood|date=4 September 2011|format=Video interview}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ricky|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|last3=Rosellini|first3=Anne|last4=Reisman|first4=Linda|last5=Harrison|first5=Anne|title=Debra Granik, Anne Rosellini, Linda Reisman & Anne Harrison Discuss \"Leave No Trace\"|url=https://www.buildseries.com/video/5b3291ffbf48853c22c34717/|work=BUILD Series|date=26 June 2018|format=Video interview}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Debra Granik|nowrap=yes}}\n* {{IMDb name|0335138}}\n\n{{Debra Granik}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Granik, Debra}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Silver Spring, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Sundance Film Festival award winners]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:People from Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Writers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Debra Granik\n| image = Debra Granik.jpg\n| alt = Granik at the 2010 Deauville American Film Festival\n| caption = Granik at the 2010 [[Deauville&nbsp;American&nbsp;Film&nbsp;Festival]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|02|06}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] U.S.}}\n| education = [[Brandeis University]]<br/>[[Tisch School of the Arts]]\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n*Film director\n*screenwriter}}\n| years_active = 1987\u2013present\n| spouse = Jonathan Scheuer\n| children = 1\n}}\n'''Debra Granik''' (born February 6, 1963) is an American filmmaker.<ref name=RafaelPiRoman-WintersBone-2011>{{cite news|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|last2=Roman|first2=Rafael Pi|title=Sunday Arts Profile: Debra Granik Interview with Rafael Pi Roman|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9SiTYdsqpY|work=Rafael Pi Roman|date=17 February 2011|format=Video interview}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-StrayDog-2014>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Kate|title=Download: Debra Granik|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/opinion/sunday/debra-granik.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1 November 2014|language=en}}</ref> She is most known for 2004's ''[[Down to the Bone (film)|Down to the Bone]],'' which starred [[Vera Farmiga]], 2010's ''[[Winter's Bone]],'' which starred [[Jennifer Lawrence]] in her breakout performance and for which Granik was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]],<ref name=VanityFair-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Sperling|first1=Nicole|title=The Filmmaker Who Directed Jennifer Lawrence's First Oscar-Nominated Role Has a New Star in Leave No Trace|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/06/debra-granik-jennifer-lawrence-thomasin-mckenzie-leave-no-trace|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=26 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> and 2018's ''[[Leave No Trace (film)|Leave No Trace]],'' a film based on the book ''My Abandonment'' by [[Peter Rock (novelist)|Peter Rock]].<ref name=Vulture-Sundance-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Buchanan|first1=Kyle|title=After Launching Jennifer Lawrence, Director Debra Granik Is Finally Back|url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/06/winters-bone-director-debra-granik-on-leave-no-trace.html|work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=27 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nGranik was born in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], to father William R. Granik, who was an attorney with [[U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development|H.U.D.]] who litigated [[fair housing]],<ref name=NYTimes-Father-HUD-1989>{{cite news|last1=Lewin|first1=Tamar|title=Children as Neighbors? Elderly Are Worried|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/11/28/us/children-as-neighbors-elderly-are-worried.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 November 1989|language=en}}</ref> and mother Brenda Granik Zusman.<ref name=WashPost-WilliamGranik-Obit-2012>{{cite news|title=William R. Granik: Notice|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/washingtonpost/obituary.aspx?fhid=10909&n=william-r-granik&pid=156052506|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> She grew up in the suburbs of [[Washington D.C.]]<ref name=HReporter-LeaveNoTrace-Interview-2018>{{cite news|last1=Kilkenny|first1=Katie|title=Director Debra Granik Explains Why It's Been Eight Long Years Between 'Winter's Bone' and Her New Film|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/director-debra-granik-explains-why-been-eight-long-years-between-winters-bone-leave-no-trace-1123551|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=29 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> Her parents divorced in 1978. \n\nGranik is the granddaughter of broadcast pioneer Ted Granik (1907\u20131970),<ref name=LC-TheodoreGranikPapers-2013>{{cite book|last1=Sullivan|first1=Joseph|last2=Miller|first2=Mike|last3=Kerwin|first3=Patrick|last4=Monagle|first4=John|title=Theodore Granik Papers (1930-1970): A Finding Aid to the Collection in the Library of Congress \u2013 MSS75822|date=2013|publisher=Manuscript Division, Library of Congress |location=Washington, D.C.|url=http://findingaids.loc.gov/exist_collections/service/mss/eadxmlmss/eadpdfmss/2013/ms013088.pdf|format=Finding aid}}</ref> founder and moderator of the long-run public affairs panel discussion program, ''[[The American Forum of the Air]],'' on from 1934 to 1956, first on the radio and later on television.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Ella|title=Debra Granik Explores the Ozarks in 'Winter's Bone'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/movies/02granik.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 April 2010|language=en}}</ref> Granik is from a [[Jewish]] family.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012>{{cite news|last1=Shebar|first1=Billy|title=Skateboarding on Hardscrabble|url=http://www.brandeis.edu/magazine/2012/summer/featured-stories/granik.html|work=Brandeis Magazine|publisher=[[Brandeis University]]|date=Summer 2012|language=en}}</ref><ref name=JewishJournal-WintersBone-Interview-2011>{{cite news|last1=Pfefferman|first1=Naomi|title=Debra Granik cuts to the emotional bone with 'Winter's Bone'|url=http://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts/89357/|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|date=18 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Granik received her B.A. in political science from [[Brandeis University]].<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=Brandeis-EnvironmentalProtection-Thesis-1984>{{cite book|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|title=Environmental Protection: A Citizens' Movement|date=1984|publisher=Brandeis University|location=Waltham, MA|url=https://search.library.brandeis.edu/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=BRAND_ALMA21206021730001921&context=L&vid=BRAND&search_scope=ALMA&tab=alma&lang=en_US|language=en|format=Senior honors thesis/dissertation|oclc=31927747}}</ref> As an undergraduate at Brandeis, Granik also took classes at the [[Studio for Interrelated Media]] at the [[Massachusetts College of Art]].<ref name=NYU-Alumni-Bio-2018 /> In 2001, Granik received an MFA from [[New York University|NYU's]] [[Tisch School of the Arts]].<ref name=NYU-SundancePremieres-2018>{{cite news|title=Features: 2018 Sundance Premieres|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/alumni/tisch-at-sundance/2018-sundance/premieres|work=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|publisher=[[New York University]]|date=2018|language=en|quote=Debra Granik '01 (MFA, Film), director/writer}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nWhile at Brandeis, Granik took Henry Felt's film and media workshop production class and volunteered with the Boston grassroots filmmaking organization Women's Video Collective.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=DP30-WintersBone-Interview-2011>{{cite news|last1=Poland|first1=David|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=DP/30: Winter's Bone, co-writer/director Debra Granik|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qbgKUW6cWQ8|work=DP/30: The Oral History Of Hollywood|date=4 September 2011|format=Video interview}}</ref> She also took film classes at the [[Studio for Interrelated Media]] at the [[Massachusetts College of Art]].<ref name=NYU-Alumni-Bio-2018 /> During this time, Granik made educational films for trade unions on subjects like workplace health and safety, one of which was made for the Massachusetts Division of Occupational Safety.<ref name=PreventingCumulativeTraumaDisorders-1990>{{cite film|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|title=It Didn't Have to Happen: Preventing Cumulative Trauma Disorders|date=1990|publisher=Massachusetts Dept. of Industrial Accidents, Office of Safety|location=Boston|type=VHS video|oclc=53200528}}</ref> Granik worked in production on educational media projects, eventually working on long form documentaries by Boston-area filmmakers before deciding to go to graduate school for filmmaking at [[New York University]].<ref name=NYU-Alumni-Bio-2018>{{cite news|title=Graduate Film: Alumni: Debra Granik|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/grad-film/alumni/debra-granik-|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|publisher=[[New York University]]|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Granik directed her first short film, ''Snake Feed,'' as her senior thesis with the mentorship of NYU film professor [[Boris Frumin]], who was instrumental in sharing his love of post-World War II European [[neorealist film]]s.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /><ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=DP30-WintersBone-Interview-2011 /> ''Snake Feed,'' which began its life as a 7-minute documentary portrait exercise, was accepted into [[Sundance Institute]]'s Lab Program for screenwriting and directing.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /> Granik workshopped and developed the short film into a feature film at the Sundance Lab.<ref name=PBS-Reel13-DownToTheBone-2010>{{cite news|last1=Pe\u00f1a|first1=Richard|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=Interview: Debra Granik, Director|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/reel-13-interview-debra-granik-director/|work=Reel 13|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting System|PBS]]|date=1 September 2010|format=Video interview}}</ref> Granik has said that ''Snake Feed'' was a work of narrative fiction, with the main characters, recovering addict Irene and her boyfriend Rick, playing dramatized versions of themselves.<ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005>{{cite news|last1=Kipp|first1=Jeremiah|title=Cutting Close to the Bone: An interview with Down To The Bone writer-director Debra Granik|url=https://www.filmmakermagazine.com/archives/online_features/cutting_close.php|work=[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]|date=21 November 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060413142519/https://www.filmmakermagazine.com/archives/online_features/cutting_close.php|archivedate=13 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the short film of ''Snake Feed'' and the story of Irene and Rick became the basis of Granik's first feature-length film, ''[[Down to the Bone (film)|Down to the Bone]],'' which was a fictionalized depiction of their struggles.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /><ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005 /> ''Down to the Bone'' is the story of an upstate New York mother who goes to rehab to kick her cocaine addiction and ends up falling in love with a nurse and descending back into her old drug habits.<ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005 /><ref name=SouthernSpaces-WintersBone-Review-2010>{{cite journal|last1=Moon|first1=Michael|last2=Talley|first2=Colin|title=Life in a Shatter Zone: Debra Granik's Film Winter's Bone|journal=[[Southern Spaces]]|date=2010|volume=6 December 2010|doi=10.18737/M73K6M|url=https://southernspaces.org/2010/life-shatter-zone-debra-graniks-film-winters-bone|language=en|issn=1551-2754}}</ref> ''Down to the Bone'' was based on an original screenplay written by Granik and her creative partner, [[Anne Rosellini]].<ref name=PBS-Reel13-DownToTheBone-2010 /><ref name=NYTimes-DownToTheBone-Review-2005>{{cite news|last1=Stevens|first1=Dana|title=Film in Review; Down to the Bone|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/25/arts/movies/film-in-review-down-to-the-bone.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=25 November 2005|language=en}}</ref> The role of the main character Irene, played by [[Vera Farmiga]], significantly raised Farmiga's profile as an actor.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 /><ref name=NYTimesMag-DownToTheBone-Farmiga-2006>{{cite news|last1=Hirschberg|first1=Lynn|title=A Film of One's Own|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/03/magazine/03actesses.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 September 2006|language=en}}</ref> ''Down to the Bone'' was shot in [[Ulster County, New York|Ulster County]] in upstate [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=RafaelPiRoman-WintersBone-2011 />\n\nGranik's second feature, 2010's ''[[Winter's Bone]]'', was an adaptation by Granik and Rosellini of the 2006 novel by [[Daniel Woodrell]].<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Review-2010>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=A. O.|title=Jennifer Lawrence in Debra Granik's Bleak Ozarks Film|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/11/movies/11winter.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=10 June 2010|language=en}}</ref> It is the story of Ree Dolly, a teenager living in the [[The Ozarks|Missouri's Ozark Mountains]] who is the sole caretaker of her two younger siblings and her catatonic mother. She is forced to hunt down her missing drug-dealing father in order to save her family from eviction.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 />\n\nThe film starred a then-unknown [[Jennifer Lawrence]] and [[John Hawkes (actor)|John Hawkes]] and won the Grand Jury Prize: Dramatic Film at the [[2010 Sundance Film Festival]], which led to a distribution deal with [[Roadside Attractions]].<ref name=IndieWire-WintersBone-Review-2010>{{cite news|last1=Kohn|first1=Eric|title=Review: Drama in Absence: Debra Granik's \"Winter's Bone\"|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2010/06/review-drama-in-absence-debra-graniks-winters-bone-245347/|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=7 June 2010}}</ref> ''Winter's Bone'' won the [[Seattle International Film Festival]] Golden Space Needle Audience Award for Best Director and Best Actress award for Jennifer Lawrence.<ref name=Seattlest-WintersBone-Interview-2010>{{cite news|last1=Mikel|first1=Amy|title=An Interview with Debra Granik, Director of Winter's Bone|url=http://seattlest.com/2010/07/01/an_interview_with_debra_granik_dire.php|work=Seattlest|publisher=[[Gothamist]]|date=1 July 2010}}</ref> In 2011, ''Winter's Bone'' was nominated for four [[83rd Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Jennifer Lawrence and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for John Hawkes.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Oscars-2011>{{cite news|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|title=The Carpetbagger: A Magical Morning in New York|url=https://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/25/a-magical-morning-in-new-york/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=25 January 2011|language=en}}</ref> The film featured a soundtrack made up of old time gospel, bluegrass, and traditional music found in the Ozarks and was produced by Steve Peters. It features the singing of Marideth Sisco, who worked as a music and folklore consultant for the region, and also appeared in the ''Winter's Bone.'' The actor [[John Hawkes (actor)|John Hawkes]] sings one track on the soundtrack.<ref name=LargeheartedBoy-WintersBoneSoundtrack-2010>{{cite news|last1=Peters|first1=Steve|title=Largehearted Boy: Soundtracked \u2013 \"Winter's Bone\" by Steve Peters|url=http://www.largeheartedboy.com/blog/archive/2010/12/soundtracked_wi.html|work=Largehearted Boy|date=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Winter's Bone'' was shot on location in the [[Ozark]] area of southern [[Missouri]]. Granik cast many of the supporting roles with first-time actors from the surrounding area and all of the homes on screen were established Ozark homes\u2014no sets were built for this film.<ref name=Seattlest-WintersBone-Interview-2010 /><ref name=AVClub-WintersBone-Interview-2010>{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Sam|title=Interview: Debra Granik|url=https://film.avclub.com/debra-granik-1798220605|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=24 June 2010}}</ref> For the look of the film, Granik kept most of the established aesthetics of the homes in which they were shooting and many of the few mementos that were added to the homes were contributed by Ozark people in the community.<ref name=SouthernSpaces-WintersBone-Review-2010 />\n\nGranik produced and directed an [[HBO]] television pilot called ''American High Life.'' The show was a family drama that \"follows a young career woman to her economically depressed small home town in the midwest.\"<ref name=IndieWire-AmHighLife-2012>{{cite news|first1=Anne|last1=Thompson|title=Exclusive: 'Winter's Bone' Director Debra Granik's Next Projects: HBO Series, Doc, Another 'Bone' Movie with Russell Banks|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/whats-next-for-winters-bone-director-debra-granik-hbo-doc-another-bone-movie-with-russell-banks|date=4 May 2012|work=[[IndieWire]]}}</ref> The show was not picked up.<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Matthew|title=Debra Granik Is The Hollywood Director Who Casts Nobodies To Capture Real Rural America|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/debra-granik-leave-no-trace_us_5b34e24be4b0b5e692f554b4|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nGranik developed a film adaption of ''[[Rule of the Bone]]'', the 1995 novel by [[Russell Banks]], but the project is still in development.<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018 />\n\nIn 2014, Granik's film, ''Stray Dog,'' was released.<ref name=NYTimes-StrayDog-Review-2015>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=A.O.|title=Review: 'Stray Dog' Documents a Complex Veteran|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/movies/review-stray-dog-documents-a-complex-veteran.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 July 2015|language=en}}</ref> The film is a documentary about a man named Ron Hall, whose nickname is \"Stray Dog,\" and portrays his life as an avid biker and Vietnam Veteran who sometimes struggles with PTSD.<ref name=LATimes-StrayDog-2014>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Amy|title=Debra Granik tells a Vietnam veteran's tale in 'Stray Dog' documentary|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-debra-granik-stray-dog-20140618-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=18 June 2014}}</ref> The film documents Hall's participation in an annual pilgrimage motorcycle ride called \"Ride to the Wall\" with fellow biker Vietnam vets from all over the country where they ride to the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /> Granik had met Hall, who had a small role on ''Winter's Bone,'' during filming.<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /><ref name=NYTimes-StrayDog-Review-2015 />\n\nGranik directed the drama ''[[Leave No Trace (film)|Leave No Trace]]'', starring [[Ben Foster]] and newcomer [[Thomasin McKenzie]], which was released in 2018, domestically by [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]] and internationally by Sony Worldwide Acquisitions.<ref name=HReporter-LeaveNoTrace-Interview-2018 /><ref name=NYU-SundanceDistro-2018>{{cite news|title=Grad Film Shines at Sundance|url=https://tisch.nyu.edu/grad-film/news/2018/grad-film-shines-at-sundance|work=[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|publisher=[[New York University]]|date=2018|language=en}}</ref> The film tells the story of a father and daughter who illegally live on government land and are forced to adapt to more traditional living in mainstream life.<ref name=Vulture-Sundance-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=LATimes-LeaveNoTrace-Feature-2018>{{cite news|last1=Olsen|first1=Mark|title=Filmmaker Debra Granik returns with drama of family and survival in 'Leave No Trace'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-sundance-debra-granik-leave-no-trace-20180123-htmlstory.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=23 January 2018}}</ref> It examines ideas of self-reliance and community, and was a critics' pick of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=NYTimes-LeaveNoTrace-Review-2018>{{cite news|last1=Dargis|first1=Manohla|title=Review: 'Leave No Trace' Is a Very American Story About Survival|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/movies/leave-no-trace-review-ben-foster.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> ''Leave No Trace'' premiered at the 2018 [[Sundance Film Festival]], and played at the [[Cannes Film Festival]], and was shot in the forested areas of [[Oregon]], including [[Forest Park (Portland, Oregon)|Forest Park]] near [[Portland, Oregon]], over the course of 30 days.<ref name=VanityFair-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=AP-LeaveNoTrace-Cannes-2018>{{cite news|last1=Coyle|first1=Jake|title=In 'Leave No Trace,' Debra Granik stays off the beaten path|url=https://apnews.com/58afc195ed7044459285d59bb06ae35b|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=25 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> In addition to Oregon, [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] was used for locations, with some scenes shot at a Christmas tree farm.<ref name=OPB-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Notarianni|first1=John|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title='Leave No Trace' Director Debra Granik On Shooting A True Oregon Film |url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/article/leave-no-trace-oregon-film-director-interview-debra-granik/|work=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|date=30 June 2018|language=en|format=Includes audio}}</ref> ''Leave No Trace'' took approximately three and a half years to develop, from the first time Granik read Peter Rock's novel, ''My Abandonment,'' on which the film was based.<ref name=BUILDseries-LeaveNoTrace-2018>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ricky|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|last3=Rosellini|first3=Anne|last4=Reisman|first4=Linda|last5=Harrison|first5=Anne|title=Debra Granik, Anne Rosellini, Linda Reisman & Anne Harrison Discuss \"Leave No Trace\"|url=https://www.buildseries.com/video/5b3291ffbf48853c22c34717/|work=BUILD Series|date=26 June 2018|format=Video interview}}</ref>\n\nOther projects Granik has in development include a documentary about life after being released from jail and the subject of [[recidivism]] in East Baltimore \u2013 that was to feature [[Felicia Pearson|Felicia \"Snoop\" Pearson]] from ''[[The Wire]]'' and elements of her memoir, ''[[Grace After Midnight]]''<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 /> \u2013 but is now a documentary about four former inmates in New York City.<ref name=ScreenDaily-NickelDimed-2018>{{cite news|last1=Kay|first1=Jeremy|title=Debra Granik's 'Nickel And Dimed' looks for partners at Cannes (exclusive)|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/debra-graniks-nickel-and-dimed-looks-for-partners-at-cannes-exclusive/5129144.article|work=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|date=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=FilmComment-FutureProjects-2018>{{cite journal|last1=Lizotte|first1=Chloe|title=News to Me: Debra Granik, Mia Hansen-L\u00f8ve, Claude Lanzmann|journal=[[Film Comment]]|date=9 July 2018|url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/news-debra-granik-mia-hansen-love-claude-lanzmann/}}</ref>\n\nAnother project is a film based on [[Barbara Ehrenreich]]'s book, ''[[Nickel and Dimed|Nickel and Dimed: On (Not) Getting By in America]],'' which focuses on poverty and the [[working poor]] in America.<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=FilmComment-FutureProjects-2018 />\n\n== Themes ==\nGranik is known for discovering actors like [[Jennifer Lawrence]]<ref name=AFI-WintersBone-Casting-2011>{{cite news|last1=Granik|first1=Debra|title=Winter's Bone Director/Co-Writer, Debra Granik on Casting the Film|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xoJj1b-GUYQ|work=[[American Film Institute]]|date=2 March 2011|format=Video interview}}</ref>, [[Vera Farmiga]] and [[Thomasin McKenzie]] who have gone on to successful careers after early roles in Granik's films. She is also known for using local, non-professional actors in her films.<ref name=VanityFair-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=PBS-Reel13-DownToTheBone-2010 /> Granik has worked with creative partner [[Anne Rosellini]] on all of her films.<ref name=BUILDseries-LeaveNoTrace-2018 />\n\nGranik has said that she sees a common thread of press coverage describing her as having a \"comeback narrative,\"<ref name=HuffPost-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /> along with questions about how much time has elapsed between projects,<ref name=BUILDseries-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /> partly due to the relatively low output of films in her career compared to the contemporaries she started out with.<ref name=Vulture-Sundance-LeaveNoTrace-2018 /><ref name=LATimes-StrayDog-2014 />\n\nInterviewed by Jeremiah Kipp in ''[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]'' in 2005, Granik discussed the challenges of directing a move like ''Down to the Bone''. She gave an overview of the challenges involved in doing a film about addiction:\n:The traditional storyline in an American film is usually in the form of a V shape. I am oversimplifying, but we see someone tumbling down, they hit bottom, and then they rise up again and find redemption. Anyone who personally, tangentially or culturally knows anything about addiction is aware that it resembles an EKG. Up and down, up and down. Very few people ever get clean on the first or second attempt. For many people, it\u2019s something they have to try over and over again. You get knocked down and ask all the ethical questions like how many chances do you give a person? When is the last chance? How many chances do they get? Can you imagine how difficult it is to fit that in a feature-length film? But those are the questions that are worth asking... The reason why boils down to the word \u201cdark\u201d. It is the scariest four-letter word in American storytelling and in this culture. Our film had a strong reception in Europe and achieved distribution, but that was not the case here. We received so many responses like, \u201cWe love the film, but we cannot do anything with it or we\u2019ll lose our shirts. We\u2019re sorry.\u201d The intervention comes from people like Laemmle/Zeller Films. Every couple of years, some mavericks take on this challenge of distributing so-called un-distributable films. They take those films on a small run and allow them to see the light of day. Those efforts are what give a film like ''Down to the Bone'' a chance to have a life of some kind.<ref name=Filmmaker-CloseToTheBone-Interview-2005 />\n\nGranik's films deal with issues of personal strength and willpower, like the character of Ree Dolly in ''[[Winter's Bone]]''. She cites [[Mike Leigh]], [[Ken Loach]], [[Shane Meadows]], the [[Dardenne brothers]], [[Laurent Cantet]], and [[Abbas Kiarostami]] as some of her major influences in her directing career.<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Feature-2010 />In an interview with [https://ff2media.com/thehotpinkpen/ FF2 Media] about ''Leave No Trace'', Granik discusses the themes of the film and what drew her to creating the film:<blockquote>I realized while reading it that one of the turning points in a girl\u2019s coming-of-age is coming to terms with the fact that as much as you may care about someone, you can\u2019t necessarily save them or even help them. You can be loving and tolerant, but you can\u2019t fix them. And that\u2019s something she\u2019s really struggling with in a really robust way, especially when they\u2019re in a new setting. And I really liked the fact that Tom is the one thing that\u2019s grounding him. She is his source of meaning. His sense of self-worth is bolstered by being meaningful to her, by being her dad. He takes pride in being her teacher and taking responsibility for her. And I was just so interested in the universality of that. The ties that bind is core material. There\u2019s nothing new about those themes, but I really liked that the novel had renewed my interest in exploring them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ff2media.com/blog/2018/06/28/modern-prospero-and-miranda-in-debra-graniks-leave-no-trace/|title=Modern Prospero and Miranda in Debra Granik\u2019s \u2018Leave No Trace\u2019|last=Coffin|first=Lesley|date=2018-06-28|website=FF2 Media|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGranik is married to Jonathan Scheuer, who has executive produced her films and is Vice Chairman of the Board of Trustees of [[National Jazz Museum in Harlem]].<ref name=LargeheartedBoy-WintersBoneSoundtrack-2010 /><ref name=NatlJazzMuseumHarlem-Board-Scheuer-2018>{{cite news|title=Who We Are: Board of Trustees|url=http://jazzmuseuminharlem.org/about-us/who-we-are/|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=[[National Jazz Museum in Harlem]]|quote=Jonathan Scheuer, Vice Chairman}}</ref> They live in New York City and have a daughter.<ref name=LATimes-StrayDog-2014 />\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 1987: ''Two in Twenty'' (TV series) for Somerville Community Access Television \u2013 director/cinematographer<ref name=BrandeisMag-Feature-2012 />\n* 1990: ''It Didn't Have to Happen: Preventing Cumulative Trauma Disorders'' (documentary) \u2013 producer<ref name=PreventingCumulativeTraumaDisorders-1990 />\n* 1997: ''Snake Feed'' (short film) \u2013 producer, writer, director, off-line editor\n* 1997; ''American Independents II: The Blinking Madonna and Other Miracles'' (short film) \u2013 conceived by<ref name=NYTimes-BlinkingMadonna-Review-1997>{{cite news|last1=James|first1=Caryn|title=Coming to Terms With Family Secrets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/12/arts/coming-to-terms-with-family-secrets.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 May 1997|language=en}}</ref>\n* 1998: ''Smear'' (short film) \u2013 boom operator\n* 1998: ''Jorge'' (short film) \u2013 assistant camera\n* 1998: ''99 Threadwaxing'' (short film) \u2013 cinematographer\n* 2002: ''Breaker'' (short film) \u2013 cinematographer\n* 2003: ''[[Thunder in Guyana]]'' (documentary) \u2013 cinematographer<ref name=PBS-IndependentLens-Guyana-2003>{{cite news|title=Thunder in Guyana: Film Credits|url=http://www.pbs.org/independentlens/thunderinguyana/credits.html|work=[[Independent Lens]]|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]|date=2003|quote=The Film: Filmmaker Suzanne Wasserman shot Thunder in Guayana between 1997 and 1999}}</ref>\n* 2004: ''[[Down to the Bone (film)|Down to the Bone]]'' \u2013 writer, director, additional photographer\n* 2005: ''[[Independent Lens]]: Thunder in Guyana/Unites States of Poetry'' \u2013 cinematographer<ref name=NYTimes-Guyana-Review-2005>{{cite news|last1=Heffernan|first1=Virginia|title=A Radical Journey From Chicago to Guyana|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/22/arts/television/a-radical-journey-from-chicago-to-guyana.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 February 2005|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''[[Winter's Bone]]'' \u2013 adapted screenplay, director\n* 2014: ''Stray Dog'' (documentary) \u2013 writer, director\n* 2015: ''[[Independent Lens]]: Stray Dog'' (documentary) \u2013 writer, director\n* 2018: ''[[Leave No Trace (film)|Leave No Trace]]'' \u2013 adapted screenplay, director\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n:{{see|List of accolades received by Winter's Bone}}\n* 1998: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[List of Sundance Film Festival award winners#1998|Honorable Mention Short Filmmaking]] for ''Snake Feed''<ref name=NYTimes-SnakeFeed-SundanceAward-1998>{{cite news|last1=Maslin|first1=Janet|title=Various Guises of Misery in Sundance Winners|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/26/movies/various-guises-of-misery-in-sundance-winners.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=26 January 1998|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2004: [[Deauville American Film Festival]], Grand Prix (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone''\n* 2004: [[Gotham Awards]], [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2010]], Breakthrough Director Award (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone''\n* 2004: [[Sundance Film Festival]], Grand Jury Prize Dramatic (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone''\n* 2004: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[List of Sundance Film Festival award winners#2004|Directing Award Dramatic]] for ''Down to the Bone''<ref name=NYTimes-DownToTheBone-Review-2005 />\n* 2005: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit John Cassavetes Award|John Cassavetes Award]] (nominated) for ''Down to the Bone'' \u2013 with Richard Lieske, Susan Leber, Anne Rosellini\n* 2010: [[Berlin International Film Festival]], [[International Confederation of Art Cinemas|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale des Cin\u00e9mas d\u2019Art et d\u2019Essai (C.I.C.A.E.)]], Forum Award for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2010: [[Berlin International Film Festival]], ''[[Tagesspiegel]],'' Readers' Jury Award for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2010: [[Deauville American Film Festival]], Prix du Jury for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 tied with ''[[The Myth of the American Sleepover]],'' directed by [[David Robert Mitchell]]\n* 2010: [[Deauville American Film Festival]], Grand Prix (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2010: [[Gotham Awards]], [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2010]], [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Feature|Best Feature]] for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini, Alix Madigan<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-GothamAwards-2010>{{cite news|last1=Ryzik|first1=Melena|title=The Carpetbagger: 'Winter's Bone' Dominates at Gothams|url=https://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/29/winters-bone-dominates-at-gothams/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=29 November 2010|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2010: [[Gotham Awards]], [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2010]], Audience Award (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini, Alix Madigan<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-GothamAwards-2010 />\n* 2010: [[Seattle International Film Festival]], Golden Space Needle Award, Best Director for ''Winter's Bone''<ref name=Seattlest-WintersBone-Interview-2010 />\n* 2010: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[List of Sundance Film Festival award winners#2010|Grand Jury Prize: Dramatic Film]] for ''Winter's Bone''<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-SundanceAwards-2010>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=The Carpetbagger: Sundance Spreads the Love|url=https://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/30/sundance-spreads-the-love/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 January 2010|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2010: [[Sundance Film Festival]], [[Waldo Salt#The Waldo Salt Screenwriting Award|Waldo Salt Screenwriting Award]], for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-SundanceAwards-2010 />\n* 2011: [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], [[83rd Academy Awards]], [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Oscars-2011 />\n* 2011: [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], [[83rd Academy Awards]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini, based on the novel by [[Daniel Woodrell]]<ref name=NYTimes-WintersBone-Oscars-2011 />\n* 2011: [[Athena Film Festival]], Director's Award for Vision and Talent for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[British Independent Film Awards]], Best Foreign Film (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[Humanitas Prize]], Sundance Film Category for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini<ref name=Humanitas-WintersBone-2011>{{cite news|title=Past Winners: 2011 Anne Rosellini & Debra Granik: Winter's Bone|url=https://www.humanitasprize.org/past-winners/|work=[[Humanitas Prize]]}}</ref>\n* 2011: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Film|Best Feature]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone''\n* 2011: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[26th Independent Spirit Awards]], [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] (nominated) for ''Winter's Bone'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini\n* 2015: [[Atlanta Film Festival]], Jury Award, Best Documentary Feature for ''Stray Dog'' \u2013 with Anne Rosellini\n* 2015: [[Independent Spirit Awards]], [[30th Independent Spirit Awards]] [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]] (nominated) for ''Stray Dog''\n* 2018: [[Seattle International Film Festival]], Grand Jury Prize (nominated) for ''Leave No Trace''\n* 2018: [[Seattle International Film Festival]], Golden Space Needle Award, Best Director (nominated) for ''Leave No Trace''\n* 2018: [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director]]\n* 2018: [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Independent Films]]\n* 2019: Inaugural Career Spotlight Award of the [[Boston Society of Film Critics]]<ref>https://bostonfilmcritics.org/blog/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite news|last1=Pe\u00f1a|first1=Richard|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=Interview: Debra Granik, Director|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/reel-13-interview-debra-granik-director/|work=Reel 13|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting System|PBS]]|date=1 September 2010|format=Video interview}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Poland|first1=David|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|title=DP/30: Winter's Bone, co-writer/director Debra Granik|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qbgKUW6cWQ8|work=DP/30: The Oral History Of Hollywood|date=4 September 2011|format=Video interview}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ricky|last2=Granik|first2=Debra|last3=Rosellini|first3=Anne|last4=Reisman|first4=Linda|last5=Harrison|first5=Anne|title=Debra Granik, Anne Rosellini, Linda Reisman & Anne Harrison Discuss \"Leave No Trace\"|url=https://www.buildseries.com/video/5b3291ffbf48853c22c34717/|work=BUILD Series|date=26 June 2018|format=Video interview}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Debra Granik|nowrap=yes}}\n* {{IMDb name|0335138}}\n\n{{Debra Granik}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Granik, Debra}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Silver Spring, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Sundance Film Festival award winners]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:People from Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Writers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters fro