to withdraw their permission for the use of [[List of compositions by Richard Strauss|his music]] after he was depicted as a [[Nazism|Nazi sympathiser]], a move that effectively banned the film from being shown again until the copyright on his work had expired.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/e057fe2977934a069dae97b01cdf652c |title=Omnibus: Dance of the Seven Veils \u2013 BBC One \u2013 15 February 1970 |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Genome |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-51676381 |title=Banned Dance of the Seven Veils gets second airing |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 February 2020 |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===March===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|As cases of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus in the UK]] continue to increase, a [[BBC One]] programme ''Coronavirus: Everything You Need to Know'' addresses questions from the public on the outbreak.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=BBC News Special \u2013 Coronavirus: Everything You Need to Know|date=2 March 2020|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000g80s/bbc-news-special-coronavirus-everything-you-need-to-know|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303115141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000g80s/bbc-news-special-coronavirus-everything-you-need-to-know|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''3'''\n|[[Sky UK|Sky]] and [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] secure a deal to make the [[Disney+]] streaming service available on [[Sky Q]] when the channel is launched later in the month.<ref>{{cite news|last=Warren |first=Tom |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/3/21162654/disney-plus-sky-q-partnership-launch-uk-ireland-release-date |title=Disney Plus to launch on Sky Q in the UK later this month |publisher=The Verge |date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''4'''\n|''[[Spitting Image]]'' co-creator [[Roger Law]] announces that it the show will return on [[BritBox]] after twenty four years.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |title=Spitting Image to return on BritBox, 24 years after the TV show ended|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51734335|accessdate=13 March 2020|date=4 March 2020|agency=BBC}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|[[Kevin Clifton]] announces he is leaving ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' after seven years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51767429 |title=Kevin Clifton to leave Strictly Come Dancing |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''7'''\n|Michael and Jowita win the second series of ''[[The Greatest Dancer]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Craig |first=David |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2020-03-08/the-greatest-dancer-2020-winners/ |title=Michael and Jowita win top prize |publisher=Radio Times |date=8 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''8'''\n|[[Joe Swash]] and dance partner [[Alex Murphy (figure skater)|Alex Murphy]] win [[Dancing on Ice (series 12)|series twelve]] of ''[[Dancing on Ice]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jessica |last=Sansome |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/tv/joe-swash-wins-dancing-ice-17887280 |title=Joe Swash wins Dancing On Ice 2020 \u2013 and fans are completely divided |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=8 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''11'''\n|Georgie Mills wins series five of ''[[Got What It Takes?]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Barbara |last=Hodgson |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/tv/cbbc-sarita-playfair-whitley-bay-17900238 |title=See the Whitley Bay teenager proving she's Got What It Takes in CBBC singing contest |publisher=Reach plc |newspaper=Evening Chronicle |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''13'''\n|''[[Sport Relief#Sport Relief 2020|Sport Relief 2020]]'' goes ahead in front of a live audience in Salford despite the cancellation of a number of other events involving the gathering of large crowds due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51872636 |title=Sport Relief: BBC charity broadcast to go ahead in Salford |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The event raises \u00a340 million by the end of the evening, with co-presenter [[Gary Lineker]] saying \"a chunk\" of the funds raised will go towards those affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51872636 |title=Sport Relief appeal raises more than \u00a340m for charities |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|ITV confirms that the following day's edition of ''[[Ant & Dec's Saturday Night Takeaway]]'' will be broadcast live and in front of a studio audience as normal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/a31483509/ant-dec-saturday-night-takeaway-continues-coronavirus/ |title=Ant & Dec's Saturday Night Takeaway continues with full audience |publisher=Digital Spy |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> However, the series finale, scheduled to be broadcast from [[Walt Disney World]] in [[Florida]] will no longer go ahead after the resort announced its intention to close as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/13/ant-decs-saturday-night-takeaway-finale-walt-disney-world-florida-cancelled-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-12396126/ |title=Saturday Night Takeaway Walt Disney World finale in Florida cancelled |newspaper=Metro |publisher= |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''14'''\n|Manchester's [[Victoria Baths]], featured in a multitude of television series such as ''[[Coronation Street]]'', ''[[Cold Feet]]'' and ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'', is to open to the public for an exhibition highlighting its use as a backdrop for television series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-manchester-51871338/manchester-s-victoria-baths-is-opening-its-doors-to-the-public?intlink_from_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fentertainment_and_arts&link_location=live-reporting-map |title=Manchester's Victoria Baths is opening its doors to the public |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''15'''\n|The government announces plans to hold daily televised press conferences to update the public on the fight against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]], starting on Monday 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51901818 |title=Coronavirus: Downing Street to give daily update on fight against outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|'''16'''\n|The BBC delays its planned changes to TV licences for the over-75s from June to August because of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|ITV announce that ''[[Coronation Street]]'' and ''[[Emmerdale]]'' will \"remind people of important public health issues\" like hand-washing because of the coronavirus pandemic. The filming schedule for both soaps has not so far been disrupted by the pandemic, but series such as ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'' and ''[[Line of Duty]]'' have delayed the filming of forthcoming series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51912510 |title=Coronavirus: Coronation Street and Emmerdale 'to remind about hand-washing' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|ITV launches Week 12 of its \"Creates\" Ident package in 2020, designed by On The Mend & NHS Staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/itvcreates/march/on-the-mend-nhs-staff |title=On The Mend & NHS Staff |publisher=ITV |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''17'''\n|The BBC announces major changes to the schedule across the network. While programmes such as ''[[Politics Live]]'', ''[[Victoria Derbyshire (TV programme)|Victoria Derbyshire]]'', ''[[The Andrew Neil Show]]'', ''[[Newswatch (British TV programme)|Newswatch]]'', ''[[The Travel Show (TV programme)|The Travel Show]]'' and ''[[HARDTalk]]'' have been suspended, others such as ''[[Newsnight]]'' and ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'' will continue with a smaller number of production staff. ''[[Question Time (TV programme)|Question Time]]'' is moved to an earlier 8pm Thursday timeslot and will be broadcast without an audience from a fixed location. Podcasts programmes ''Americast'', ''Beyond Today'' and ''The Next Episode'' are also suspended.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=BBC News sets out plans to keep audiences receiving trusted and accurate information |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/news-coronavirus |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> \n|-\n|rowspan=6|'''18'''\n|The [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Eurovision Song Contest]], scheduled to be held in [[Rotterdam]] in May, is permanently cancelled because of the ongoing coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51870325 |title=Eurovision Song Contest 2020 cancelled over coronavirus |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|The BBC announces that due to the coronavirus pandemic, filming on ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', ''[[EastEnders]]'', ''[[Holby City]]'', ''[[Pobol y Cwm]]'' and ''[[River City]]'' is suspended until further notice. Weekly episodes of ''EastEnders'' will also be reduced from four to two to keep it on the air for as long as possible. <ref name=EastEnders>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/entertainment-arts-51943592|title=Coronavirus: EastEnders, Casualty, Doctors and Holby City suspend filming|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|The BBC says that it will show more educational programmes to cater for children not attending school, and that it is in talks with the [[Department for Education (United Kingdom)|Department for Education]] and schools to support [[GCSE]] and [[A Level]] curriculums with extra programmes on [[BBC Four]] and the [[BBC Red Button]] service.<ref>{{cite news|first=Dave |last=Speck |url=https://www.tes.com/news/coronavirus-bbc-works-schools-offer-tv-lessons |title=Coronavirus: BBC works with schools to offer TV lessons |newspaper=Times Educational Supplement |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|ITV announce that the filming schedule for ''[[Coronation Street]]'' will change from the week beginning 30 March, with the number of weekly episodes reduced from six to three. ''[[Emmerdale]]'' will also change its pattern from the usual six episodes to five. <ref name=EastEnders/>\n|-\n|The semi-final of the [[The Voice UK (series 9)|ninth series]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', scheduled for Saturday 28 March, is postponed until later in the year, while the 21 March edition of ''Ant & Dec's Saturday Night Takeaway'' will go ahead without a live studio audience.<ref name=Revamp>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51931050 |title=Coronavirus: BBC and ITV revamp broadcast plans amid outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|The BBC and ITV announce major revamps of their schedules to include a weekly programme giving the public information about the coronavirus pandemic; the BBC will also air more programmes focused on health, fitness, education, religion and food recipes.<ref name=Revamp/>\n|-\n|'''19'''\n|Fitness expert [[Diana Moran]], known as the Green Goddess when she presented keep fit sessions on ''[[BBC Breakfast Time]]'' during the 1980s, is to make a return to breakfast television to give fitness advice to people in self-isolation because of the coronavirus pandemic. She will present a slot on ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' three times a week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933762 |title=Coronavirus: How to exercise while staying at home |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|'''20'''\n|The BBC brings forward [[Malory Towers (TV series)|its adaptation]] of [[Enid Blyton]]'s ''[[Malory Towers]]'' series by two weeks, making it available on BBC iPlayer from Monday 23 March. The series is also scheduled to begin airing on the [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC channel]] from April.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tara Conlan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/20/downton-for-kids-bbc-brings-forward-malory-towers-adaptation |title='Downton for kids': BBC brings forward Malory Towers adaptation |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Filming on the scripted reality television show ''[[The Only Way is Essex]]'' is suspended temporarily because of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-51976924 |title=Coronavirus: The Only Way is Essex postpones filming |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|It is reported that the organisers of the Eurovision Song Contest are looking at staging an alternative event for 2020 to \"honour the songs and artists\" who would have appeared in the contest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51984359 |title='Alternative Eurovision' being planned after 2020's contest was cancelled |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''22'''\n|ITV announces that filming on ''Coronation Street'' and ''Emmerdale'' will be temporarily halted from Monday 23 March. Its daytime programmes ''[[Lorraine (TV series)|Lorraine]]'' and ''[[Loose Women]]'' will also temporarily cease live broadcasting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-22/coronavirus-coronation-street-emmerdale-suspend-production-coronavirus-fears/ |title=Lorraine and Loose Women to stop live broadcasting as Coronation Street and Emmerdale suspend filming |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''23'''\n|In a televised address, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the coronavirus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2010| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2010| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=\nBoris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| publisher=The Guardian| date=23 March 2010| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Overnight viewing figures indicate the address, the first such Prime Ministerial broadcast since that by [[Tony Blair]] at the time of the [[Iraq War]] in 2003, to have been watched by a collective audience of at least 27.1 million viewers, placing it high on the [[list of most watched television broadcasts in the United Kingdom]] with the greatest number since the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52018502 |title=Coronavirus: 27.1 million watch PM Boris Johnson's TV address |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> ITV revises its previous decision and announces that ''Emmerdale'' will now broadcast only three times a week from 30 March.\n|-\n|DisneyLife closes and is replaced by [[Disney+]].\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''24'''\n|BBC News announces that it is delaying plans to cut 450 news jobs due to the pressure of covering the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52035875 |title=BBC News suspends 450 job cuts to ensure Covid-19 coverage |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Disney+]] launches in the UK, featuring ''[[The Mandalorian]]'', ''[[High School Musical: The Series]]'', ''[[Forky Asks a Question]]'' and more. It is also the first streaming service in the UK to feature ''[[The Simpsons]]'' after [[Sky UK|Sky]] and [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] secured a deal to make [[Disney+]] available on [[Sky Q]].\n|-\n|rowspan=4|'''26'''\n|''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' celebrates its 20th anniversary with a 60-minute episode.<ref>{{cite news|first=Zoe |last=Chamberlain |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/showbiz-tv/behind-scenes-bbc-tv-show-17369697 |title=Behind the scenes of BBC TV show Doctors in Birmingham on 20th anniversary |work=Birmingham Mail |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=8 December 2019 |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> The episode sees the return of [[Julia Parsons]] ([[Diane Keen]]) after eight years.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Jones|first=Alison|